nemaScore]]'''\n|-\n|-\n| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| 49% (184 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw/|title=Saw|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 46 (32 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw/critic-reviews|title=Saw (2004): Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| C+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web | title = CinemaScore | url = https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ | website = [[CinemaScore]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Saw II]]''\n| 37% (122 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_ii/|title=Saw II|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 40 (28 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-ii/critic-reviews|title=Saw II (2005): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw III]]''\n| 28% (92 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_3/|title=Saw III|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 48 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iii/critic-reviews|title=Saw III (2006): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| 20% (81 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/|title=Saw IV|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| 36 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iv/critic-reviews|title=Saw IV (2007): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw V]]''\n| 13% (76 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_v/|title=Saw V|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20 (13 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-v/critic-reviews|title=Saw V (2008): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|C<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| 39% (72 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_VI/|title=Saw VI|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n| 30 (12 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-vi/critic-reviews|title=Saw VI (2009): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 24, 2009}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| 10% (79 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw3d/|title=Saw 3D|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n| 24 (17 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-3d/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Saw 3D (2010)|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B\u2013<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| 33% (87 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jigsaw_2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| 39 (18 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jigsaw|website=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|}\n\n==Other media==\n{{main|List of Saw media}}\n\n===Video games===\n[[Japan]]ese video game company [[Konami]] currently owns the rights to the ''Saw'' interactive video game property. Konami stated in mid-2009 that they wanted to make ''Saw'' a series of video games to supplement the films. They also wish to make ''Saw'' their next big survival horror franchise next to their other property, ''[[Silent Hill]]''. They stated that because ''Saw'' focuses on visual intensity and ''Silent Hill'' focuses on psychological terror, both could exist in the video game industry without directly competing against each other.<ref name= \"Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?\">{{cite news|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/the_cut_scene/2009/04/silent-hill-say-hello-to-your-new-brother-jigsawkonami-has-confirmed-an-earlier-cut-scene-report-that-it-has-bought-the-pub.html|title=Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?|work=The Cut Scene|date=2009-04-02|access-date=2009-08-04}}</ref>\n\nThe first game in the series, ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'', set between the first and second film in the series, was initially released on October 6, 2009.<ref name=WanWhannell>{{Cite web|url=http://www.360-hq.com/article-2382-thread-1-0.html|title=Producer James Wan On Saw The Video Game &#124; 360-HQ.COM|website=www.360-hq.com|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Nick|last=Wingfield|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118092768266523504 |title=A Start Up's Risky Niche: Movie-Based Videogames|date=2007-06-04|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2008-01-30|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/848/848533p1.html|title=Saw announced|access-date=2008-01-30}}</ref> with a sequel ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'', released on October 19, 2010, for the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3, ten days before the release of the seventh film, ''Saw 3D''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/57520/Jigsaw_Returns.php|title=Jigsaw Returns!|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]|date=April 9, 2010|access-date=April 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[David Tapp]] and [[Amanda Young]] were released as part of the downloadable ''Saw Chapter'' for the video game ''[[Dead by Daylight]]''.<ref name= \"Dead by Daylight\">{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/01/22/dead-by-daylight-saw-dlc-confirmed-jigsaw-coming-tomorrow/|publisher=Comic Book|title=Dead By Daylight Confirms Saw DLC, Releasing Tomorrow|date=2018-01-22|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Comic books===\n''Saw: Rebirth'', a [[comic book]] prequel to the original film released to promote ''Saw II''. Its [[canon (fiction)|canonicity]] was later contradicted by events in ''Saw IV''. It is, however, the first canonical appearance of Jigsaw's wife, Jill, who was later introduced into the film series in ''Saw III'', and established still-canonical elements of Jigsaw's backstory (an engineer who is dying from brain cancer.)\n\n===Theme park attractions===\n* \"[[Saw: The Ride]]\" is a [[Gerstlauer Euro-Fighter]] roller coaster themed around the franchise, which opened on March 13, 2009, at [[Thorpe Park]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. It features an enclosed dark ride section with special effects, before cars travel outside and are pulled up a 100-foot vertical lift hill into a steep 100-degree drop.\n* [[Thorpe Park]] opened a temporary ''Saw'' attraction called \"Saw \u2014 Movie Bites\" for their 2009 Fright Nights event.\n* It was announced in October 2009 that Thorpe Park would also be adding a permanent, year-round [[live action]] horror [[maze]] themed around the ''Saw'' movies. It opened at the start of the 2010 season, and features six scenes representing one iconic trap from each movie to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hauntedattractions.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=570&Itemid=2|title=Thorpe: SAW Alive exclusive details|work=Haunted Attractions|publisher=hauntedattractions.co.uk|access-date=2009-11-29}}</ref>\n* \"[[Halloween Horror Nights|Saw: Game Over]]\" was a 2009 maze made by [[Universal Parks & Resorts|Universal Studios]] for [[Halloween Horror Nights]], based on characters, traps and scenes from the films.<ref name= \"Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11469|publisher=Shock Till You Drop|title=Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!|date=2009-08-19|access-date=2009-11-12}}</ref> At the [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] rendition of Horror Nights it was titled ''Saw: Game Over'', while at the [[Universal Studios Florida]] rendition, it was simply titled ''Saw''.\n* \"Saw\", a themed haunted house, operated during the month of October at [http://www.frightdome.com Fright Dome], [[Circus Circus Las Vegas]]. It featured interactive, handcrafted replicas of the \"games\" set by [[Jigsaw Killer|Jigsaw]]. It was introduced in 2009 and partnered with [[Lionsgate]] and [[Twisted Pictures]].\n* In 2010, \"[[Halloween Fright Nights]]\" at [[Warner Bros. Movie World]] featured a maze created by [[Sudden Impact Entertainment]], featuring characters, traps and scenes from the films. The maze was simply titled \"Saw Maze\".\n* \"Saw Haunted Attraction\" was a maze at the Brea Plaza Shopping Center in 2008 created by Sinister Pointe Haunted Attractions.\n* \"SAWMANIA\" was a fan event in New York. Eventgoers were able to meet actors and directors, and view props used in the films.\n\n=== Fan films universe ===\n''Main article: [[Saw fan films universe]]''\n\nThe impact of the ''Saw'' films inspired creators from all over the world to create [[fan film]]s based on the franchise. The films are in no way affiliated with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate films]] or [[Twisted Pictures]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[Splatter film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Saw (franchise)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n; Databases\n* [http://allmovie.com/work/saw-film-series-356901 ''Saw'' film series] at [[Allmovie]]\n* [http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=Saw.htm ''Saw'' film series] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n; Official sites\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041126235053/http://www.sawmovie.com/ ''Saw'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071002065430/http://www.saw2.com/ ''Saw II'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061116073244/http://saw3.com/ ''Saw III website''] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024161726/http://movies.break.com/saw4/ ''Saw IV'' website] (archive)\n* [http://www.saw5.com ''Saw V'' website]\n; Other links\n* [http://www.thorpepark.com/ Thorpe Park] - home to two ''Saw'' attractions\n* [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/scott-mendelson/goodbye-john-a-farewell-t_b_775552.html?view=print Goodbye John: A Farewell to Saw, as Jigsaw Lays His Last Trap] by Scott Mendelson\n\n{{Saw}}\n\n[[Category:Film franchises introduced in 2004]]\n[[Category:Horror film franchises]]\n[[Category:Splatter films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:Saw (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate franchises]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n", "name_user": "Acekard", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saw_(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "3M bookshelf game series", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|Series of board games and card games}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = August 2012}}\n\nThe '''3M bookshelf game series''' is a set of classic and original strategy and economic games published in the 1960s and early 1970s by [[3M]] Corporation.  The games were packaged in leatherette-look large hardback book size boxes in contrast to the prevalent wide flat game boxes.  The series grew to encompass almost three dozen games.  Most were multi-player board games or card games; a few were trivia games or 2-handed board games.  'Acquire' and 'TwixT' were among the best known and most popular titles.  The series later became part of the [[Avalon Hill]] Bookcase games. Very few of these games are still being published.<ref>Acquire by Hasbro/Avalon, Twixt by an Avalon licensee, Facts in Five and Executive Decision by University Games.</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThese games were marketed towards adults and were designed to fit onto a standard bookshelf.  Each game fit into a slip cover that was made to resemble the spine of a [[hardcover]] book.  3M's catalog described them as follows: \"bookcase games, packaged in attractive leather-like slipcases, make a handsome set of volumes for any bookshelf.\" The line consisted of republished classics such as [[Go (board game)|Go]], [[Chess]] and [[Backgammon]] as well as original games.  The Bookshelf games were originally in large boxes (8.5\"x12\"x2.25\"); later, a series in smaller boxes called \"gamettes\" was introduced. (The early ones were packaged in a different shape box called a \"butterbox\".)\n3M also published two other series of games in the same time frame: the Sports series (1966) and the Paper games series (1974).  These were not in the bookshelf packaging format.\n\nAcquire, TwixT and Sleuth were inducted into ''Games Magazine'''s Hall of Fame in the mid-1980s, though Sleuth was later dropped (1991) due to lack of current production.\n\nIn 1962, 3M commissioned game designers [[Alex Randolph]] and [[Sid Sackson]] to design the early games and they were largely responsible for shaping the direction of the line towards abstract strategy and economic games.  Randolph eventually produced TwixT, Oh-Wah-Ree, Breakthru, Evade, Jati and Mad Mate.  Sackson contributed Acquire, Bazaar, Monad, Executive Decision, Sleuth, and Venture.  3M thereafter relied extensively on freelance designers for the later bookshelf games.  Between 400 and 600 submissions were received every year by the company.  These were screened to find unique and interesting games that were connected to any recent trends or fads.\n\nThe games were produced by [[3M]] from 1962 to 1975, under the complete company name, The Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Company. (This is printed in each box and on the instructions and some paper game pieces.) Only a small number of the games (about 10) were significant commercial successes.\n\nBy the middle 1970s, gaming trends had shifted to pen and paper [[role playing game]]s  and the 3M game division was suffering losses.  In 1976, the entire line was sold to [[Avalon Hill]], which produced a competing line of bookcase games.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arneson|first1=Erik|title=Hasbro - Brief History|url=http://boardgames.about.com/od/companies/a/hasbro_history.htm|website=About Board Games|publisher=About.com|accessdate=July 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415170800/http://boardgames.about.com/od/companies/a/hasbro_history.htm|archive-date=2008-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Avalon Hill discontinued most of them, but continued to publish some<ref>Acquire, Challenge Golf, Executive Decision, Facts-in-Five, Feudal, Oh Wah Ree, Point of Law, Sleuth, Stocks and Bonds, TwixT, Venture</ref> until 1998, when it was sold by its parent company to [[Hasbro]].<ref name=bs>{{cite news|last1=Leffall|first1=J.|title=Monarch Avalon to sell game unit to Hasbro In wake of loss, local company to get $6 million in cash|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-08-05/business/1998217009_1_avalon-hasbro-monarch-services|accessdate=August 5, 2015|work=Baltimore Sun|date=August 5, 1998}}</ref> While Acquire was mildly re-themed and published by Hasbro/Avalon Hill in 2000,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arneson|first1=Erik |title=Game History: Acquire |url=http://boardgames.about.com/od/gamehistories/p/acquire.htm |website=About Board Games|publisher=About.com |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> the company has indicated that they have no plans to publish any of the 3M or Avalon Hill bookshelf games.\n\nSince 2008, Acquire has been published by a Hasbro subsidiary, [[Wizards of the Coast]]. TwixT is still published by a German company under license.\n\nA few of the games that were not acquired by Hasbro, such as [[Facts in Five]] and [[Executive Decision (board game)|Executive Decision]] have since been published by [[University Games]] in a bookshelf format.  Like the 3M series, they are designed to mimic the appearance of a large hardcover book, but instead of a slip-case, the games use a magnetic closing flap.\n\nThis theme was later echoed in the Hasbro/[[Parker Brothers]] Vintage Game Collection games circa 2005 in hardback book design wooden boxes sold through Target stores (a different set of games than those in the 3M series).\n\n==List of games==\nThe bookshelf games series included the following games,<ref name=Gamepile>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamepile.com/items.php?id=2 |last=Matheson |first=Dennis |title=3M Games |work=The Game Pile |accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref> as well as 2 unpublished games: [[Options (board game)|Options]] and a chess variant called Mad Mate:<ref>later published as Neo-chess by Abacusspiele</ref><ref name=BGG>{{Cite web |url=http://boardgamegeek.com/wiki/page/3M_Bookshelf_Series |title=3M Bookshelf Series |work=Board Game Geek |accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref>\n<!-- Please don't add undefined (red) wikilinks here, they're useless -->\n\n'''Bookshelf''' series\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* [[Acquire]]<ref name=\"The General\">{{cite journal|title=The General Index and Company History|journal=The General Magazine Index and Company History|date=1980|url=https://archive.org/stream/GeneralMagazine_GeneralIndexVolumes1to16/General%20Index%20Volumes%201%20to%2016#page/n3/mode/2up|pages=12\u201313|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> 3 - 6 player board game\n* [[Backgammon]]<ref name=\"The General\"/>  2 player board game \n* Bazaar 2 - 6 player token trading game \n* [[Breakthru (board game)|Breakthru]][Hnefatafl]  2 player board game \n* Challenge Bridge <ref name=\"The General\"/> 4 player tournament simulation card game  \n* Challenge Football<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player simulation dice/card game \n* Challenge Golf at Pebble Beach <ref name=\"The General\"/> 1 - 4 player simulation dice game\n* [[Chess]]<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player board game\n* [[Contigo (board game)|Contigo]]<ref name=\"The General\"/>[Mancala] 2 - 4 player board game\n{{col-3}}\n* Events 4 - 8 player trivia game  \n* Executive Decision<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 6 player board game\n* [[Facts in Five]] 2+ player trivia game  \n* [[Feudal (game)|Feudal]] <ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 or 4 sides, 2 - 6 player board game  \n* Foil<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 4 player card game   \n* [[Go (board game)|Go]] <ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player board game\n* High Bid 2 - 4 player card and dice game\n* Image<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 6 player card game   \n* Jati 2-handed board game (prototype only<ref>Spielbox republished Jati in 1986</ref>)\n{{col-3}}\n* Jumpin 2 player board game\n* Mr. President 2 - 4 player card game  \n* Oh-Wah-Ree<ref name=\"The General\"/>[Mancala] 2 - 4 player board game\n* Phlounder 2 - 6 player board game  \n* [[Ploy (board game)|Ploy]]<ref name=\"The General\"/>  [chess] 2 or 4 player board game  \n* [[Point of Law (board game)|Point of Law]]  2+ player trivia game \n* Quinto 2-4 player board game  \n* Stocks & Bonds<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 8 player card game\n* [[TwixT]]<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player board game\n{{col-end}}\n<!-- Please don't add undefined (red) wikilinks here, they're useless -->\n'''Gamette''' series\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''Evade'' 2 player board game\n* ''Foil'' \n* ''High Bid'' dice and card game\n* ''Monad'' 2 - 4 player card game  \n* ''Octrix'' [bridge] 2 -4 player card game  \n* ''Sleuth''<ref name=\"The General\"/><ref>Originally published as The Case of the Elusive Assassin by Ideal in 1967</ref> card game \n* ''Sum Up'' card game\n* ''Tryce'' [rummy] card game\n* ''Venture''<ref name=\"The General\"/> card game\n}}\n<!-- Please don't add undefined (red) wikilinks here, they're useless -->\nNotes:\n\n1. Foil and High Bid were both full size bookshelf games and gamette games.\n\n2. if game was recognizable derivative of classic game, name of classic game is in brackets\n\n3. games with \"boards\" not essential for play are classified as card games or trivia games\n\n===Contigo===\n'''''Contigo''''' is an abstract strategy board game for 4 players related to both [[mancala]] and [[checkers]].  It was designed by [[Frank Thibault]], a freelance game designer, and published in 1974. The game takes approximately 45 minutes to play and is suggested for ages 12 and up. It is played by four players according to the original rules, but can still be played with only two. ''Contigo'' has a 6x6 board that is surrounded by pits, much like the ones in the game ''Mancala''. Pebbles are transferred from pit to pit. The number of pebbles in a row/ column/ diagonal's pits controls how the pawns on the board move.\n\nThere are two sets of rules used to play ''Contigo''. In the first supplied set, players try to be the first to align four of their pawns in any six space row. The row can be created either horizontally, vertically, or diagonally, without opposing pawns between them. In the more advanced set of rules, ''Contigo'' becomes a capture game. In this set, the players try to capture their opponents' key pawns.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Acquire game.JPG|[[Acquire]]\nFile:Breakthru board.png|[[Breakthru (board game)|Breakthru]]\nFile:Feudal 3M Overview.png|[[Feudal (game)|Feudal]]\nFile:Twixtboard185132.jpg|[[TwixT]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Eurogame]], a style of gaming inspired by the 3M bookshelf games\n*[[List of Avalon Hill games]], which the 3M games became part of\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{bgg|2545|''Contigo''}}\n\n{{3M bookshelf games}}\n\n[[Category:History of board games]]\n[[Category:3M Bookshelf games| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|Series of board games and card games}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = August 2012}}\n\nThe '''3M bookshelf game series''' is a set of classic and original strategy and economic games published in the 1960s and early 1970s by [[3M]] Corporation.  The games were packaged in leatherette-look large hardback book size boxes in contrast to the prevalent wide flat game boxes.  The series grew to encompass almost three dozen games.  Most were multi-player board games or card games; a few were trivia games or 2-handed board games.  'Acquire' and 'TwixT' were among the best known and most popular titles.  The series later became part of the [[Avalon Hill]] Bookcase games. Very few of these games are still being published.<ref>Acquire by Hasbro/Avalon, Twixt by an Avalon licensee, Facts in Five and Executive Decision by University Games.</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThese games were marketed towards adults and were designed to fit onto a standard bookshelf.  Each game fit into a slip cover that was made to resemble the spine of a [[hardcover]] book.  3M's catalog described them as follows: \"bookcase games, packaged in attractive leather-like slipcases, make a handsome set of volumes for any bookshelf.\" The line consisted of republished classics such as [[Go (board game)|Go]], [[Chess]] and [[Backgammon]] as well as original games.  The Bookshelf games were originally in large boxes (8.5\"x12\"x2.25\"); later, a series in smaller boxes called \"gamettes\" was introduced (the early ones were packaged in a different shape box called a \"butterbox\").\n3M also published two other series of games in the same time frame: the Sports series (1966) and the Paper games series (1974).  These were not in the bookshelf packaging format.\n\nAcquire, TwixT and Sleuth were inducted into ''Games Magazine'''s Hall of Fame in the mid-1980s, though Sleuth was later dropped (1991) due to lack of current production.\n\nIn 1962, 3M commissioned game designers [[Alex Randolph]] and [[Sid Sackson]] to design the early games and they were largely responsible for shaping the direction of the line towards abstract strategy and economic games.  Randolph eventually produced TwixT, Oh-Wah-Ree, Breakthru, Evade, Jati and Mad Mate.  Sackson contributed Acquire, Bazaar, Monad, Executive Decision, Sleuth, and Venture.  3M thereafter relied extensively on freelance designers for the later bookshelf games.  Between 400 and 600 submissions were received every year by the company.  These were screened to find unique and interesting games that were connected to any recent trends or fads.\n\nThe games were produced by [[3M]] from 1962 to 1975, under the complete company name, The Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Company (this is printed in each box and on the instructions and some paper game pieces). Only a small number of the games (about 10) were significant commercial successes.\n\nBy the middle 1970s, gaming trends had shifted to pen and paper [[role playing game]]s  and the 3M game division was suffering losses.  In 1976, the entire line was sold to [[Avalon Hill]], which produced a competing line of bookcase games.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arneson|first1=Erik|title=Hasbro - Brief History|url=http://boardgames.about.com/od/companies/a/hasbro_history.htm|website=About Board Games|publisher=About.com|accessdate=July 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415170800/http://boardgames.about.com/od/companies/a/hasbro_history.htm|archive-date=2008-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Avalon Hill discontinued most of them, but continued to publish some<ref>Acquire, Challenge Golf, Executive Decision, Facts-in-Five, Feudal, Oh Wah Ree, Point of Law, Sleuth, Stocks and Bonds, TwixT, Venture</ref> until 1998, when it was sold by its parent company to [[Hasbro]].<ref name=bs>{{cite news|last1=Leffall|first1=J.|title=Monarch Avalon to sell game unit to Hasbro In wake of loss, local company to get $6 million in cash|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-08-05/business/1998217009_1_avalon-hasbro-monarch-services|accessdate=August 5, 2015|work=Baltimore Sun|date=August 5, 1998}}</ref> While Acquire was mildly re-themed and published by Hasbro/Avalon Hill in 2000,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arneson|first1=Erik |title=Game History: Acquire |url=http://boardgames.about.com/od/gamehistories/p/acquire.htm |website=About Board Games|publisher=About.com |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> the company has indicated that they have no plans to publish any of the 3M or Avalon Hill bookshelf games.\n\nSince 2008, Acquire has been published by a Hasbro subsidiary, [[Wizards of the Coast]]. TwixT is still published by a German company under license.\n\nA few of the games that were not acquired by Hasbro, such as [[Facts in Five]] and [[Executive Decision (board game)|Executive Decision]] have since been published by [[University Games]] in a bookshelf format.  Like the 3M series, they are designed to mimic the appearance of a large hardcover book, but instead of a slip-case, the games use a magnetic closing flap.\n\nThis theme was later echoed in the Hasbro/[[Parker Brothers]] Vintage Game Collection games circa 2005 in hardback book design wooden boxes sold through Target stores (a different set of games than those in the 3M series).\n\n==List of games==\nThe bookshelf games series included the following games,<ref name=Gamepile>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamepile.com/items.php?id=2 |last=Matheson |first=Dennis |title=3M Games |work=The Game Pile |accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref> as well as 2 unpublished games: [[Options (board game)|Options]] and a chess variant called Mad Mate:<ref>later published as Neo-chess by Abacusspiele</ref><ref name=BGG>{{Cite web |url=http://boardgamegeek.com/wiki/page/3M_Bookshelf_Series |title=3M Bookshelf Series |work=Board Game Geek |accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref>\n<!-- Please don't add undefined (red) wikilinks here, they're useless -->\n\n'''Bookshelf''' series\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* [[Acquire]]<ref name=\"The General\">{{cite journal|title=The General Index and Company History|journal=The General Magazine Index and Company History|date=1980|url=https://archive.org/stream/GeneralMagazine_GeneralIndexVolumes1to16/General%20Index%20Volumes%201%20to%2016#page/n3/mode/2up|pages=12\u201313|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> 3 - 6 player board game\n* [[Backgammon]]<ref name=\"The General\"/>  2 player board game \n* Bazaar 2 - 6 player token trading game \n* [[Breakthru (board game)|Breakthru]][Hnefatafl]  2 player board game \n* Challenge Bridge <ref name=\"The General\"/> 4 player tournament simulation card game  \n* Challenge Football<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player simulation dice/card game \n* Challenge Golf at Pebble Beach <ref name=\"The General\"/> 1 - 4 player simulation dice game\n* [[Chess]]<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player board game\n* [[Contigo (board game)|Contigo]]<ref name=\"The General\"/>[Mancala] 2 - 4 player board game\n{{col-3}}\n* Events 4 - 8 player trivia game  \n* Executive Decision<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 6 player board game\n* [[Facts in Five]] 2+ player trivia game  \n* [[Feudal (game)|Feudal]] <ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 or 4 sides, 2 - 6 player board game  \n* Foil<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 4 player card game   \n* [[Go (board game)|Go]] <ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player board game\n* High Bid 2 - 4 player card and dice game\n* Image<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 6 player card game   \n* Jati 2-handed board game (prototype only<ref>Spielbox republished Jati in 1986</ref>)\n{{col-3}}\n* Jumpin 2 player board game\n* Mr. President 2 - 4 player card game  \n* Oh-Wah-Ree<ref name=\"The General\"/>[Mancala] 2 - 4 player board game\n* Phlounder 2 - 6 player board game  \n* [[Ploy (board game)|Ploy]]<ref name=\"The General\"/>  [chess] 2 or 4 player board game  \n* [[Point of Law (board game)|Point of Law]]  2+ player trivia game \n* Quinto 2-4 player board game  \n* Stocks & Bonds<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 - 8 player card game\n* [[TwixT]]<ref name=\"The General\"/> 2 player board game\n{{col-end}}\n<!-- Please don't add undefined (red) wikilinks here, they're useless -->\n'''Gamette''' series\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''Evade'' 2 player board game\n* ''Foil'' \n* ''High Bid'' dice and card game\n* ''Monad'' 2 - 4 player card game  \n* ''Octrix'' [bridge] 2 -4 player card game  \n* ''Sleuth''<ref name=\"The General\"/><ref>Originally published as The Case of the Elusive Assassin by Ideal in 1967</ref> card game \n* ''Sum Up'' card game\n* ''Tryce'' [rummy] card game\n* ''Venture''<ref name=\"The General\"/> card game\n}}\n<!-- Please don't add undefined (red) wikilinks here, they're useless -->\nNotes:\n\n1. Foil and High Bid were both full size bookshelf games and gamette games.\n\n2. if game was recognizable derivative of classic game, name of classic game is in brackets\n\n3. games with \"boards\" not essential for play are classified as card games or trivia games\n\n===Contigo===\n'''''Contigo''''' is an abstract strategy board game for 4 players related to both [[mancala]] and [[checkers]].  It was designed by [[Frank Thibault]], a freelance game designer, and published in 1974. The game takes approximately 45 minutes to play and is suggested for ages 12 and up. It is played by four players according to the original rules, but can still be played with only two. ''Contigo'' has a 6x6 board that is surrounded by pits, much like the ones in the game ''Mancala''. Pebbles are transferred from pit to pit. The number of pebbles in a row/ column/ diagonal's pits controls how the pawns on the board move.\n\nThere are two sets of rules used to play ''Contigo''. In the first supplied set, players try to be the first to align four of their pawns in any six space row. The row can be created either horizontally, vertically, or diagonally, without opposing pawns between them. In the more advanced set of rules, ''Contigo'' becomes a capture game. In this set, the players try to capture their opponents' key pawns.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Acquire game.JPG|[[Acquire]]\nFile:Breakthru board.png|[[Breakthru (board game)|Breakthru]]\nFile:Feudal 3M Overview.png|[[Feudal (game)|Feudal]]\nFile:Twixtboard185132.jpg|[[TwixT]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Eurogame]], a style of gaming inspired by the 3M bookshelf games\n*[[List of Avalon Hill games]], which the 3M games became part of\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{bgg|2545|''Contigo''}}\n\n{{3M bookshelf games}}\n\n[[Category:History of board games]]\n[[Category:3M Bookshelf games| ]]\n", "name_user": "Emeraldcrown", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:syntactical revisions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/3M_bookshelf_game_series"}
{"title_page": "Experience machine", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=December 2010}}\nThe '''experience machine''' or '''pleasure machine''' is a thought experiment put forward by  philosopher [[Robert Nozick]] in his 1974 book  ''[[Anarchy, State, and Utopia]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nozick | first = Robert | title = Anarchy, state, and utopia | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York | year = 1974 | isbn = 0-465-09720-0 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/anarchystateutop00nozi/page/42 42\u201345] | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/anarchystateutop00nozi/page/42 }}</ref> It is one of the best known attempts to refute ethical [[hedonism]], and does so by imagining a choice between everyday reality and an apparently preferable [[simulated reality]].\n\nIf the primary thesis of hedonism is that \"pleasure is the good\", then any component of life that is not pleasurable does nothing directly to increase one's [[well-being]]. This is a view held by many value theorists, but most famously by some classical [[Utilitarianism|utilitarians]]. Nozick attacks the thesis by means of a [[thought experiment]]. If he can show that there is something other than pleasure that has value and thereby increases our well-being, then hedonism is defeated.\n\n==The thought experiment==\nNozick asks us to imagine a machine that could give us whatever desirable or pleasurable experiences we could want. Psychologists have figured out a way to stimulate a person's brain to induce pleasurable experiences that the subject could not distinguish from those he would have apart from the machine. He then asks, if given the choice, would we prefer the machine to real life?\n\nNozick also believes that if pleasure were the only intrinsic value, people would have an overriding reason to be hooked up to an \"experience machine,\" which would produce favorable sensations.\n\n===Initial concerns===\nWho would run the machines if everyone plugs in? Nozick asks us to ignore this concern, since it does not adversely affect the thought experiment. One could simply stipulate that the machines have been so well designed as to be fail-proof.\n\nThe experiment is also open to multiple interpretations. For instance, Nozick claims that you could either map out the rest of your life in the machine before plugging in, or you could unplug periodically to choose your programming for the next cycle. While interesting, these variations do not directly affect the argument either.\n\n===The argument===\nThe argument is along these lines:\n\n*P1: If experiencing as much pleasure as we can is all that matters to us, then if we will experience more pleasure by doing x than by doing y, we have no reason to do y rather than x.\n*P2: We will experience more pleasure if we plug into the experience machine than if we do not plug into the experience machine.\n*C1: If all that matters to us is that we experience as much pleasure as we can then we have no reason not to plug into the experience machine. (P1&P2)\n*P3: We have reason not to plug into the experience machine.\n*C2: Experiencing as much pleasure as we can is not all that matters to us. (C1&P3, by [[Modus tollens|MT]])\n\n===Reasons not to plug in===\nNozick provides us with three reasons not to plug into the machine.\n\n# ''We want to'' do ''certain things, and not just have the experience of doing them.''\n#* \"It is only because we first want to do the actions that we want the experiences of doing them.\" (Nozick, 43)\n# ''We want to'' be ''a certain sort of person.''\n#* \"Someone floating in a tank is an indeterminate blob.\" (Nozick, 43)\n# ''Plugging into an experience machine limits us to a man-made reality (it limits us to what we can make).''\n#* \"There is no ''actual'' contact with any deeper reality, though the experience of it can be simulated.\" (Nozick, 43)\n\n===Counterarguments===\nPsychologist and philosopher Joshua Greene says that our intuitions about the experience machine may be affected by [[status quo bias]], and suggests reformulating the thought experiment in a form which counters this.<ref name=\"Lazari-RadekSinger2014\">{{cite book|author1=Katarzyna de Lazari-Radek|author2=[[Peter Singer]]|title=The Point of View of the Universe: Sidgwick and Contemporary Ethics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x2NeAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257|date=22 May 2014|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-102242-5|pages=257}}</ref> According to his version:\n<blockquote> \nyou wake up in a plain white room. You are seated in a reclining chair with a steel contraption on your head. A woman in a white coat is standing over you. 'The year is 2659,' she explains, 'The life with which you are familiar is an experience machine program selected by you some forty years ago. We at IEM interrupt our client's programs at ten-year intervals to ensure client satisfaction. Our records indicate that at your three previous interruptions you deemed your program satisfactory and chose to continue. As before, if you choose to continue with your program you will return to your life as you know it with no recollection of this interruption. Your friends, loved ones, and projects will all be there. Of course, you may choose to terminate your program at this point if you are unsatisfied for any reason. Do you intend to continue with your program?\n</blockquote>\nIf we feel differently about this version of the story compared to the form that Nozick offers, according to Greene this is due to [[status quo bias]].<ref name=\"Lazari-RadekSinger2014\"/>\n\n==In fiction==\n{{See also|Simulated reality in fiction}}\nBefore it became a philosophical thought experiment in the mid seventies, the pleasurable but simulated experience versus reality dilemma had been a staple of science fiction; for example in the short story \"[[The Chamber of Life]]\" by [[Green Peyton Wertenbaker]] ([[:fr:Green Peyton Wertenbaker|fr]]) , published in the magazine ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' in October 1929. The novel ''[[Infinite Jest]]'' by [[David Foster Wallace]] involves a similar formulation of the experience machine. The novel revolves around a film titled ''Infinite Jest'' that is lethally pleasurable: the film is so entertaining that, once watched, the viewer will desire nothing else but to watch the film over and over.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sloane |first=Peter |year=2014 |title=The Divided Selves of David Foster Wallace |journal=Tropos |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=67-73 |doi=10.14324/111.2057-2212.011 |url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1420208/}}</ref> Examples of movies centering on machines capable of replaying experiences previously recorded include the 1983 film ''[[Brainstorm (1983 film)|Brainstorm]]'' and the 1995 film ''[[Strange Days (film)|Strange Days]]''.<ref name=\"Baggott2005\">{{cite book|author=[[Jim Baggott]]|title=A Beginner's Guide to Reality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9yAa7kRYiUkC&pg=PT137|date=1 September 2005|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-0-14-104232-9|pages=137}}</ref>\n\nIt also is a running theme of the 1999 film ''[[The Matrix]]''.<ref name=\"Grau2005\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Grau|title=Philosophers Explore The Matrix|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Pmld5FXZ0YC&pg=PA18|year=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-518107-4|pages=18\u2013}}</ref> [[Agent Smith]]'s account of the early history of the Matrix includes the idea that humans reject a virtual reality that offers them paradise; however, later his informant  [[List of minor characters in the Matrix series#Mr. Reagan.2FCypher|Cypher]] is willing to betray his colleagues because he would prefer to be reinserted into an (arguably less perfect) Matrix as a wealthy and successful man than continue to live in the harsh realities outside the simulation. While this later version of the Matrix is not a paradise-like reality in the literal sense, it may be argued that it is a lot like a pleasure-inducing experience machine, since Cypher is given the opportunity to have a prominent position of power and wealth in this new simulation. As he says while dining at a simulated restaurant: <blockquote>\"You know, I know this steak doesn't exist. I know that when I put it in my mouth, the Matrix is telling my brain that it is juicy, and delicious. After nine years, you know what I realize? Ignorance is bliss.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://thematrixtruth.remoteviewinglight.com/html/transcript-of-the-matrix-5.html\n |title        = The Matrix Transcript Part 05\n |work         = The Matrix\n |publisher    = The Matrix Truth\n |accessdate   = June 22, 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716044256/http://thematrixtruth.remoteviewinglight.com/html/transcript-of-the-matrix-5.html\n |archive-date = July 16, 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Wirehead (science fiction)#Known Space stories|Droud]], a pleasure-inducing device in [[Known Space]] stories\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Experience Machine, The}}\n[[Category:Philosophical arguments]]\n[[Category:Internalism and externalism]]\n[[Category:Thought experiments in ethics]]\n[[Category:Hyperreality]]\n[[Category:Thought experiments in philosophy]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=December 2010}}\nThe '''experience machine''' or '''pleasure machine''' is a thought experiment put forward by  philosopher [[Robert Nozick]] in his 1974 book  ''[[Anarchy, State, and Utopia]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nozick | first = Robert | title = Anarchy, state, and utopia | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York | year = 1974 | isbn = 0-465-09720-0 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/anarchystateutop00nozi/page/42 42\u201345] | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/anarchystateutop00nozi/page/42 }}</ref> It is one of the best known attempts to refute ethical [[hedonism]], and does so by imagining a choice between everyday reality and an apparently preferable [[simulated reality]].\n\nIf the primary thesis of hedonism is that \"pleasure is the good\", then any component of life that is not pleasurable does nothing directly to increase one's [[well-being]]. This is a view held by many value theorists, but most famously by some classical [[Utilitarianism|utilitarians]]. Nozick attacks the thesis by means of a [[thought experiment]]. If he can show that there is something other than pleasure that has value and thereby increases our well-being, then hedonism is defeated.\n\n==The thought experiment==\nNozick asks us to imagine a machine that could give us whatever desirable or pleasurable experiences we could want. Psychologists have figured out a way to stimulate a person's brain to induce pleasurable experiences that the subject could not distinguish from those he would have apart from the machine. He then asks, if given the choice, would we prefer the machine to real life?\n\nNozick also believes that if pleasure were the only intrinsic value, people would have an overriding reason to be hooked up to an \"experience machine,\" which would produce favorable sensations.\n\n===Initial concerns===\nWho would run the machines if everyone plugs in? Nozick asks us to ignore this concern, since it does not adversely affect the thought experiment. One could simply stipulate that the machines have been so well designed as to be fail-proof.\n\nThe experiment is also open to multiple interpretations. For instance, Nozick claims that you could either map out the rest of your life in the machine before plugging in, or you could unplug periodically to choose your programming for the next cycle. While interesting, these variations do not directly affect the argument.\n\n===The argument===\nThe argument is along these lines:\n\n*P1: If experiencing as much pleasure as we can is all that matters to us, then if we will experience more pleasure by doing x than by doing y, we have no reason to do y rather than x.\n*P2: We will experience more pleasure if we plug into the experience machine than if we do not plug into the experience machine.\n*C1: If all that matters to us is that we experience as much pleasure as we can then we have no reason not to plug into the experience machine. (P1&P2)\n*P3: We have reason not to plug into the experience machine.\n*C2: Experiencing as much pleasure as we can is not all that matters to us. (C1&P3, by [[Modus tollens|MT]])\n\n===Reasons not to plug in===\nNozick provides us with three reasons not to plug into the machine.\n\n# ''We want to'' do ''certain things, and not just have the experience of doing them.''\n#* \"It is only because we first want to do the actions that we want the experiences of doing them.\" (Nozick, 43)\n# ''We want to'' be ''a certain sort of person.''\n#* \"Someone floating in a tank is an indeterminate blob.\" (Nozick, 43)\n# ''Plugging into an experience machine limits us to a man-made reality (it limits us to what we can make).''\n#* \"There is no ''actual'' contact with any deeper reality, though the experience of it can be simulated.\" (Nozick, 43)\n\n===Counterarguments===\nPsychologist and philosopher Joshua Greene says that our intuitions about the experience machine may be affected by [[status quo bias]], and suggests reformulating the thought experiment in a form which counters this.<ref name=\"Lazari-RadekSinger2014\">{{cite book|author1=Katarzyna de Lazari-Radek|author2=[[Peter Singer]]|title=The Point of View of the Universe: Sidgwick and Contemporary Ethics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x2NeAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257|date=22 May 2014|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-102242-5|pages=257}}</ref> According to his version:\n<blockquote> \nyou wake up in a plain white room. You are seated in a reclining chair with a steel contraption on your head. A woman in a white coat is standing over you. 'The year is 2659,' she explains, 'The life with which you are familiar is an experience machine program selected by you some forty years ago. We at IEM interrupt our client's programs at ten-year intervals to ensure client satisfaction. Our records indicate that at your three previous interruptions you deemed your program satisfactory and chose to continue. As before, if you choose to continue with your program you will return to your life as you know it with no recollection of this interruption. Your friends, loved ones, and projects will all be there. Of course, you may choose to terminate your program at this point if you are unsatisfied for any reason. Do you intend to continue with your program?\n</blockquote>\nIf we feel differently about this version of the story compared to the form that Nozick offers, according to Greene this is due to [[status quo bias]].<ref name=\"Lazari-RadekSinger2014\"/>\n\n==In fiction==\n{{See also|Simulated reality in fiction}}\nBefore it became a philosophical thought experiment in the mid seventies, the pleasurable but simulated experience versus reality dilemma had been a staple of science fiction; for example in the short story \"[[The Chamber of Life]]\" by [[Green Peyton Wertenbaker]] ([[:fr:Green Peyton Wertenbaker|fr]]) , published in the magazine ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' in October 1929. The novel ''[[Infinite Jest]]'' by [[David Foster Wallace]] involves a similar formulation of the experience machine. The novel revolves around a film titled ''Infinite Jest'' that is lethally pleasurable: the film is so entertaining that, once watched, the viewer will desire nothing else but to watch the film over and over.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sloane |first=Peter |year=2014 |title=The Divided Selves of David Foster Wallace |journal=Tropos |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=67-73 |doi=10.14324/111.2057-2212.011 |url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1420208/}}</ref> Examples of movies centering on machines capable of replaying experiences previously recorded include the 1983 film ''[[Brainstorm (1983 film)|Brainstorm]]'' and the 1995 film ''[[Strange Days (film)|Strange Days]]''.<ref name=\"Baggott2005\">{{cite book|author=[[Jim Baggott]]|title=A Beginner's Guide to Reality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9yAa7kRYiUkC&pg=PT137|date=1 September 2005|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-0-14-104232-9|pages=137}}</ref>\n\nIt also is a running theme of the 1999 film ''[[The Matrix]]''.<ref name=\"Grau2005\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Grau|title=Philosophers Explore The Matrix|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Pmld5FXZ0YC&pg=PA18|year=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-518107-4|pages=18\u2013}}</ref> [[Agent Smith]]'s account of the early history of the Matrix includes the idea that humans reject a virtual reality that offers them paradise; however, later his informant  [[List of minor characters in the Matrix series#Mr. Reagan.2FCypher|Cypher]] is willing to betray his colleagues because he would prefer to be reinserted into an (arguably less perfect) Matrix as a wealthy and successful man than continue to live in the harsh realities outside the simulation. While this later version of the Matrix is not a paradise-like reality in the literal sense, it may be argued that it is a lot like a pleasure-inducing experience machine, since Cypher is given the opportunity to have a prominent position of power and wealth in this new simulation. As he says while dining at a simulated restaurant: <blockquote>\"You know, I know this steak doesn't exist. I know that when I put it in my mouth, the Matrix is telling my brain that it is juicy, and delicious. After nine years, you know what I realize? Ignorance is bliss.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://thematrixtruth.remoteviewinglight.com/html/transcript-of-the-matrix-5.html\n |title        = The Matrix Transcript Part 05\n |work         = The Matrix\n |publisher    = The Matrix Truth\n |accessdate   = June 22, 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716044256/http://thematrixtruth.remoteviewinglight.com/html/transcript-of-the-matrix-5.html\n |archive-date = July 16, 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Wirehead (science fiction)#Known Space stories|Droud]], a pleasure-inducing device in [[Known Space]] stories\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Experience Machine, The}}\n[[Category:Philosophical arguments]]\n[[Category:Internalism and externalism]]\n[[Category:Thought experiments in ethics]]\n[[Category:Hyperreality]]\n[[Category:Thought experiments in philosophy]]\n", "name_user": "Monsieur D.", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experience_machine"}
{"title_page": "Ratatouille (film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ratatouille\n| image          = RatatouillePoster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| border         = yes\n| alt            = Remy, a rat, smiles nervously as he clings onto a piece of cheese while he is pinned to a door by sharp knives and forks. The film's tagline, \"He's dying to become a chef\", is displayed along the top. A logo with the film's title and pronunciation is shown at the bottom, with the dot on the 'i' in \"Ratatouille\" doubling as a rat's nose with whiskers and a chef's toque.\n| director       = [[Brad Bird]]\n| producer       = [[Brad Lewis]]\n| screenplay     = Brad Bird\n| story          = {{unbulleted list|[[Jan Pinkava]]|Jim Capobianco|Brad Bird}}\n| music          = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Patton Oswalt]]\n* [[Ian Holm]]\n* [[Lou Romano]]\n* [[Janeane Garofalo]]\n* [[Brad Garrett]]\n* [[Peter O'Toole]]\n* [[Brian Dennehy]]\n* [[Peter Sohn]]\n* [[Will Arnett]]\n}}\n| cinematography = {{unbulleted list|[[Sharon Calahan]]|Robert Anderson}}\n| editing        = {{unbulleted list|[[Darren T. Holmes]]|Stan Webb}}\n| studio         = {{unbulleted list|[[Walt Disney Pictures]]|[[Pixar Animation Studios]]}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures Distribution]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|6|22|[[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theatre]]|2007|6|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 111 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $150&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Cieply|title=It's Not a Sequel, but It Might Seem Like One After the Ads|work=The New York Times|date=April 24, 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/24/movies/24orig.html}}</ref>\n| gross          = $620.7&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ratatouille.htm |title=Ratatouille (2007) |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 4, 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Ratatouille''''' is a 2007 American [[computer-animated]] [[comedy film]] produced by [[Pixar]] and released by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. It was the eighth film produced by [[Pixar]], and was written and directed by [[Brad Bird]], who took over from [[Jan Pinkava]] in 2005, and produced by [[Brad Lewis]], from an original idea from Pinkava, Bird, and Jim Capobianco. The title refers to the French dish [[ratatouille]], which is served at the end of the film and also references the animal type of the main character, a rat. The plot follows a [[rat]] named Remy, who dreams of becoming a chef and tries to achieve his goal by forming an alliance with a Parisian restaurant's garbage boy. \n\nThe film stars the voices of [[Patton Oswalt]] as Remy, an [[anthropomorphic]] [[rat]] who is interested in cooking; [[Lou Romano]] as Alfredo Linguini, a young garbage boy who befriends Remy; [[Ian Holm]] as Skinner, the head chef of Auguste Gusteau's restaurant; [[Janeane Garofalo]] as Colette Tatou, a [[r\u00f4tisseur]] at Gusteau's restaurant and the staff's only female chef; [[Peter O'Toole]] as Anton Ego, a restaurant critic; [[Brian Dennehy]] as Django,  Remy's father and leader of his clan; [[Peter Sohn]] as Emile, Remy's older brother; and [[Brad Garrett]] as Auguste Gusteau, a recently deceased chef.\n\nThe development of ''Ratatouille'' began in 2000 when Pinkava wrote the original concepts of the film. In 2005, following Pinkava's departure from Pixar, Bird was approached to direct the film and revise the story. Bird and some of the film's crew members also visited Paris for inspiration. To create the food animation used in the film, the crew consulted chefs from both France and the United States. Lewis interned at [[Thomas Keller]]'s [[The French Laundry]] restaurant, where Keller developed the [[confit byaldi]], a dish used in the film. [[Michael Giacchino]] composed the Paris-inspired music for the film.\n\n''Ratatouille'' premiered on June 22, 2007, at the [[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], with its general release June 29, 2007, in the United States. The film grossed  $620.7 million and was a box office success. It received critical acclaim for Giacchino's score, voice acting, writing, and the animation. The film won the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]] and was nominated for four more, including [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]. It was later voted one of the 100 greatest motion pictures of the 21st century by a [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century|2016 poll of international critics]] conducted by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=The 21st Century's 100 greatest films |publisher=BBC |date=August 23, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nRemy is a highly intelligent and idealistic young rat with unusually acute senses of taste and smell, who dreams of becoming a chef like his idol, the late Auguste Gusteau. However, the rest of his colony, including his brother Emile and his father Django, are interested in food only for sustenance. One day, when the colony is forced to flee their home because of Remy and Emile's wild encounter with the homeowner whose ceiling housed their colony, Remy is separated from the clan and eventually finds himself above the kitchen of Gusteau's Restaurant in Paris.\n\nWhen Remy observes a young garbage boy named Alfredo Linguini attempt to fix a soup he has spilled, he recognizes that Linguini is unintentionally ruining it and fixes his mistakes. Linguini catches him in the act, but does not reveal him to Skinner, Gusteau's former [[sous-chef]] and new owner of the restaurant. Skinner confronts Linguini for tampering with the soup, but when the soup is accidentally served to a critic and proves to be a success, Colette Tatou, the staff's only female chef, convinces Skinner to retain Linguini. Skinner spots Remy trying to escape, and orders Linguini to kill the rat, but Linguini decides to keep Remy instead. \n\nWhen Linguini is ordered to replicate the soup, he is helped by Remy. Skinner, having tried the soup, decides to retain Linguini. Back in Linguini's apartment the two learn to communicate and devise a plan:  Remy hides under Linguini's [[toque]] at the restaurant and guides his movements like a [[marionette]] by pulling on his hair. Skinner orders Colette to teach Linguini to be a cook.\n\nRemy witnesses Skinner's discovery that Linguini is Gusteau's illegitimate son and rightful owner of the restaurant, and gives the evidence to Linguini, who forces Skinner out. The restaurant thrives as Remy's recipes become popular, though as Linguini and Colette develop a relationship, Remy begins to feel left out. He reunites with Emile and the clan, but is rejected by Django over his admiration for humans.\n\nThe dour world-renowned food critic Anton Ego, whose negative review had indirectly led to Gusteau's death, announces he will once again dine at the restaurant. After an argument with Linguini, Remy leads his clan to raid the restaurant's pantries in revenge, but Linguini drives them out. Remy is captured by Skinner, who intends to use his talents to create a line of frozen food products, but is promptly freed by Django and Emile. Linguini apologizes to Remy, having been unable to cook without him, and reveals the truth to his staff, but they all leave, heartbroken and in disbelief. Colette returns after recalling Gusteau's motto, \"Anyone can cook.\"\n\nImpressed by Remy's determination, Django and the clan offer to help, and cook under Remy's direction while Linguini waits tables. Skinner attempts to interfere, but is bound, gagged, and banished from the restaurant. Remy creates a variation on [[ratatouille]] which reminds Ego of his mother's cooking. Humbled and delighted by the dish, Ego asks to meet the chef, so Linguini and Colette wait until the other diners have left before introducing Remy. Ego is stunned and writes a glowing review, saying how he now understands Gusteau's famous motto, and indirectly calling Remy \"nothing less than the finest chef in France.\"\n\nDespite the review, the restaurant is shut down due to the presence of the rats, causing Ego to lose his job and credibility as a critic. However, he now funds and frequents a popular new bistro, ''La Ratatouille,'' run by Remy, Linguini, and Colette as the rat colony settles into their new home in the bistro's attic.\n\n==Voice cast==\n<!-- This section is meant to contain introductions only. It is not meant to include major plot elements. Please refrain from including such information -->\n{{div col|colwidth=}}\n\n*[[Patton Oswalt]] as Remy, a rat with heightened senses of taste and smell, enabling a talent and desire for cooking. Director Brad Bird chose Oswalt after hearing his food-related comedy routine.<ref name=\"moryvisit\">{{cite news |author=Drew McWeeny |title=Moriarty Visits Pixar To Chat With Brad Bird And Patton Oswalt About RATATOUILLE! |publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |date=May 21, 2007 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/32729 |accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Ian Holm]] as Chef Skinner, a diminutive chef and the owner of Auguste Gusteau's restaurant. Since Gusteau's death, Skinner has used the Gusteau name to market a line of cheap microwaveable meals. Skinner's behavior, diminutive size, and [[body language]] are loosely based on [[Louis de Fun\u00e8s]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.telemoustique.be/cps/rde/xchg/tm/hs.xsl/magazine_ratatouille.html?archive_numero=4254 |title=Ratatouille, le film |publisher=Telemoustique |date=August 8, 2007 |language=French|accessdate=December 22, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071211061319/http://www.telemoustique.be/cps/rde/xchg/tm/hs.xsl/magazine_ratatouille.html?archive_numero=4254 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = December 11, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Lou Romano]] as Alfredo Linguini, the son of Auguste Gusteau and Renata Linguini, and a hapless garbage boy who befriends Remy. He is named after [[Alfredo Ferrari]], the son of Italian automaker [[Enzo Ferrari]].\n*[[Janeane Garofalo]] as Colette Tatou, Gusteau's ''[[chef de partie|r\u00f4tisseur]]''. She is inspired by French chef [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Darroze]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Molly|last2=Gavard|first2=Corinne|title=A Taste of Whimsy Wows the French|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/13/AR2007081300990.html|accessdate=November 16, 2014|work=The Washington Post|date=August 14, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Brad Garrett]] as Auguste Gusteau, France's most famous chef, who died a broken heart following a negative review by Anton Ego. Many reviewers believe that Gusteau is inspired by real-life chef [[Bernard Loiseau]], who committed suicide after media speculation that his flagship restaurant, La C\u00f4te d'Or, was going to be downgraded from three [[Michelin Guide|Michelin stars]] to two.<ref>{{cite news |author=Molly Moore and Corinne Gavard |title=A Taste of Whimsy Wows the French |work=The Washington Post |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/13/AR2007081300990.html |accessdate=August 14, 2007 | date=August 14, 2007}}</ref> La&nbsp;C\u00f4te d'Or was one of the restaurants visited by Brad Bird and others in France.<ref name=\"parlez\"/>\n*[[Peter O'Toole]] as Anton Ego, a restaurant critic whose negative review led to Gusteau's five-star restaurant being downgraded to four. His appearance was modeled after [[Louis Jouvet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lesoir.be/culture/cinema/louis-de-funes-louis-jouvet-2007-08-01-542527.shtml |title=Louis De Fun\u00e8s, Louis Jouvet, Charles De Gaulle... Le jour de gloire est arriv\u00e9. Et au diable les \" freedom fries \" ! |publisher=Lesoir.be |language=French |date=August 1, 2007 |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102035303/http://www.lesoir.be/culture/cinema/louis-de-funes-louis-jouvet-2007-08-01-542527.shtml |archivedate=January 2, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Brian Dennehy]] as Django,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.scribd.com/document/6695691/Ratatouille-Script|title=Ratatouille Script|website=Scribd|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>  Remy and Emile's father, and the leader of the rats.\n*[[Peter Sohn]] as Emile, Remy's gluttonous older brother.\n*[[Will Arnett]] as Horst, Skinner's German [[sous chef]].\n*Julius Callahan as Lalo, Gusteau's ''[[saucier]]'' and ''poissonnier''. Callahan also voices Fran\u00e7ois, the advertising executive handling the marketing of Gusteau's microwaveable products.\n*[[James Remar]] as Larousse, Gusteau's ''chef [[garde manger]]''.\n*[[John Ratzenberger]] as Mustafa, Gusteau's ''chef de salle''.\n*[[Teddy Newton]] as Talon Labarthe, Skinner's lawyer.\n*Tony Fucile as Pompidou, Gusteau's ''[[patissier]]''. Fucile also voices Nadar Lessard, a [[health inspector]] employed by Skinner.\n*[[Jake Steinfeld]] as Git, a former lab rat and member of Django's colony.\n*[[Brad Bird]] as Ambrister Minion, Anton Ego's butler.\n*[[St\u00e9phane Roux (actor)|St\u00e9phane Roux]] as the narrator of the cooking channel.\n*[[Thomas Keller]], the restaurateur, as a dining patron who asks \"what's new\".<ref name=\"sfcarticle\"/> In other-language versions, this role is also voiced by a chef.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Jan Pinkava]] came up with the concept in 2000, creating the original design, sets and characters and core storyline, but he was never formally named the director of the film.<ref>{{cite web | author = Leo N. Holzer | title = Pixar cooks up a story | work = The Reporter | date = June 29, 2007 | url = http://www.thereporter.com/billboard/ci_6260970 | accessdate = June 29, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070702164407/http://www.thereporter.com/billboard/ci_6260970# | archive-date = July 2, 2007 | url-status=dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> By 2004, Pixar added [[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]] as a co-director and was given exclusive control of the story.{{sfn|Price|2008|p=249}} Lacking confidence in the story development,<ref>{{cite news|author=Steve Daly |title=Brad Bird cooks up \"Ratatouille\" |work=Entertainment Weekly |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20166944_20166964_20043277_2,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506073932/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C20166944_20166964_20043277_2%2C00.html |archivedate=May 6, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Incredibles]]'' director [[Brad Bird]] was approached by Pixar management to direct the film, taking over Pinkava's role in 2005 while Peterson left the film to work on ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''.<ref name=\"early taste\">{{cite news | author=Bill Desowitz | title = Brad Bird Offers an Early Taste of Ratatouille | publisher=Animation World Magazine | date = April 25, 2007 | url = https://www.awn.com/animationworld/brad-bird-offers-early-taste-ratatouille | accessdate=May 22, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Jim Hill | title = Why For did Disney struggle to come up with a marketing campaign for Pixar's latest picture? Because the Mouse wasn't originally supposed to release \"Ratatouille\" | publisher=Jim Hill Media | date = June 28, 2007 | url = http://jimhillmedia.com/blogs/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/28/toon-thursday-why-did-disney-struggle-to-come-up-with-a-ratatouille-marketing-campaign-because-the-mouse-wasn-t-supposed-to-release-this-particular-pixar-film.aspx | accessdate =July 1, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/26/AR2007062601251.html | title = Pixar Perfectionists Cook `Ratatouille' |work=The Washington Post | date = June 26, 2007 | accessdate =January 15, 2008 | first = David | last = Germain }}</ref>{{sfn|Price|2008|p=250}} Bird was attracted to the film because of the outlandishness of the concept and the conflict that drove it: that rats feared kitchens, yet a rat wanted to work in one.<ref name=\"moryvisit\"/> Bird was also delighted that the film could be made a highly [[physical comedy]],<ref name=\"early taste\"/> with the character of Linguini providing endless fun for the animators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Linguini a la Carte |publisher=Yahoo! |date=May 22, 2007 |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |accessdate=May 23, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526103543/http://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |archivedate=May 26, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Bird rewrote the story, with a change in emphasis. He killed off Gusteau, gave larger roles to Skinner and Colette,<ref>{{cite news | author=Helen O'Hara | title = First Look: Ratatouille | work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] | page = 62 | date = June 28, 2007}}</ref> and also changed the appearance of the rats to be less [[anthropomorphic]].<ref name=\"ignedit\">{{cite web | author = Scott Collura & Eric Moro | title = Edit Bay Visit: Ratatouille | website = IGN | date = April 25, 2007 | url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/783/783392p1.html | accessdate = May 22, 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091109104953/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/783/783392p1.html | archivedate = November 9, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBecause ''Ratatouille'' is intended to be a romantic, lush vision of Paris, giving it an identity distinct from previous Pixar films,<ref name=\"early taste\"/> director Brad Bird, producer Brad Lewis and some of the crew spent a week in the city to properly understand its environment, taking a motorcycle tour and eating at five top restaurants.<ref name=\"parlez\">{{cite web|title=Parlez-vous Francais |publisher=Yahoo! |date=May 22, 2007 |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |accessdate=May 23, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526103543/http://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |archivedate=May 26, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> [[Peter Dinklage]] was offered the role of Skinner, but he turned down the role. [[Ian Holm]] was cast as the character since Bird saw him on [[The Lord of the Rings (film trilogy)|''The Lord of the Rings'' trilogy]]. There are also many water-based sequences in the film, one of which is set in the sewers and is more complex than the [[blue whale]] scene in ''[[Finding Nemo]]''. One scene has Linguini wet after jumping into the [[Seine]] to fetch Remy. A Pixar employee (Shade/Paint department coordinator Kesten Migdal) jumped into Pixar's swimming pool wearing a chef's uniform and apron to see which parts of the suit stuck to his body and which became translucent from water absorption.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Technical Ingredients |publisher=Disney Pictures | url=http://disney.go.com/disneypictures/ratatouille/main.html |accessdate=May 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Confit byaldi 1.jpg|thumb|The film's take on the traditional ratatouille dish was designed by gourmet chef Thomas Keller and later came to be known as [[confit byaldi]].]]\nA challenge for the filmmakers was creating computer-generated images of food that would appear delicious. Gourmet chefs in both the U.S. and France were consulted,<ref name=\"ignedit\"/> and animators attended cooking classes at [[San Francisco Bay Area|San Francisco-area]] culinary schools to understand the workings of a [[commercial kitchen]].<ref name=\"sfcarticle\">{{cite news | accessdate=June 29, 2007 | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/06/28/MNGGIQNA7M1.DTL |work=San Francisco Chronicle | date=June 28, 2007 | author=Stacy Finz | title=Bay Area flavors food tale: For its new film 'Ratatouille,' Pixar explored our obsession with cuisine}}</ref> Sets/Layout department manager Michael Warch, a culinary-academy-trained professional chef before working at Pixar, helped teach and consult animators as they worked. He also prepared dishes used by the Art, Shade/Paint, Effects and Sets Modeling departments.<ref name=\"cook 101\">{{cite web | title=Cooking 101 | publisher=Disney Pictures |url=http://disney.go.com/disneypictures/ratatouille/main.html |accessdate=May 23, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"nytfood\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/13/dining/13rata.html?ex=1339387200&en=988ed2df8b9bcdb4&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss |author=Kim Severson |date=June 13, 2007| title=A Rat With a Whisk and a Dream |accessdate=June 30, 2007 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> Renowned chef [[Thomas Keller]] allowed producer Brad Lewis to intern in his [[French Laundry]] kitchen. For the film's [[Climax (narrative)|climax]], Keller designed a fancy, layered version of the title dish for the rat characters to cook, which he called \"[[confit byaldi]]\" in honor of the [[Imam bayildi|original Turkish name]].<ref name=\"sfcarticle\"/> The same [[Subsurface scattering|sub-surface light scattering]] technique that was used on the skin in ''[[The Incredibles]]'' was used on fruits and vegetables,<ref name=\"animated edit\"/> while new programs gave an organic texture and movement to the food.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cooking Up CG Food |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=May 24, 2007 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=20608 |accessdate=May 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526042435/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=20608 |archivedate=May 26, 2007 }}</ref> Completing the illusion were music, dialogue, and [[abstract imagery]] representing the characters' mental sensations while appreciating food. The visual flavor [[metaphor]]s were created by animator [[Michel Gagn\u00e9]] inspired by the work of [[Oscar Fischinger]] and [[Norman McLaren]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gagneint.com/Final%20site/Animation/Pixar/Ratatouille.htm |author=Michel Gagn\u00e9|publisher=Gagne International |title=Taste Visualization for Pixar's Ratatouille |accessdate=July 9, 2007}}</ref>\nTo create a realistic compost pile, the Art Department photographed fifteen different kinds of produce, such as [[apple]]s, berries, [[banana]]s, [[mushroom]]s, [[Orange (fruit)|oranges]], [[broccoli]], and [[lettuce]], in the process of rotting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.radiofree.com/reviews/ratatoui.shtml |publisher=Radio Free Entertainment |title=Ratatouille (review) |accessdate=July 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe cast members strove to make their French accents authentic yet understandable. [[John Ratzenberger]] notes that he often segued into an Italian accent.<ref name=\"parlez\"/> According to Pixar designer Jason Deamer, \"Most of the characters were designed while Jan [Pinkava] was still directing\u2026 He has a real eye for sculpture.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Barbara Robertson |title=Fish, Rats, Chefs and Robots |publisher=CGSociety |url=http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4144 |accessdate=July 7, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808015610/http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4144# |archive-date=August 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to Pinkava, the critic Anton Ego was designed to resemble a [[vulture]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Bruce R. Miller |title=Book shows how 'Ratatouille' was made |work=Sioux City Journal |date=June 30, 2007 |url=http://www.siouxcityjournal.com/articles/2007/06/29/entertainment/local/8eead5ae7d53b500862573070071c572.txt |accessdate=June 30, 2007}}</ref> To save time, human characters were designed and animated without toes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canmag.com/nw/8040-ratatouille-concept-art-fun-facts |title=Ratatouille Concept Art and Fun Facts! |publisher=CanMag |date=June 16, 2007 |accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRat expert Debbie Ducommun (a.k.a. the \"Rat Lady\") was consulted on rat [[Habit (biology)|habits]] and characteristics.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rat fanciers hope animated film will help their pets shed bad PR |author=Cynthia Hubert |date=June 22, 2007 |work=[[Sacramento Bee]]}}</ref> Along with Ducommun's insight a [[vivarium]] containing pet rats sat in a hallway for more than a year so animators could study the movement of the animals' [[fur]], noses, ears, [[paw]]s, and [[tail]]s as they ran.<ref name=\"animated edit\">{{cite news |author=Anne Neumann |title=Ratatouille Edit Bay Visit! |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=April 25, 2007 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=19939 | accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPromotional material for [[Intel]] credits their platform for a 30 percent performance improvement in rendering software. They used Remy in some of their marketing materials.<ref>{{cite news |last=Desowitz |first=Bill |title=Intel Helps Disney/Pixar Cook Up Ratatouille |url=http://www.awn.com/news/films/intel-helps-disneypixar-cook-ratatouille |accessdate=October 6, 2015 |journal=[[Animation World Network]] |date=July 3, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Desowitz |first=Bill |url=http://www.awn.com/articles/production/iratatouillei-pixar-style-ibon-appetiti/page/2%2C1 |title=Ratatouille Pixar Style: Bon App\u00e9tit |publisher=Animation World Network |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 6, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012034021/http://www.awn.com/articles/production/iratatouillei-pixar-style-ibon-appetiti/page/2%2C1 |archivedate=October 12, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Ratatouille\n| type         = Film score\n| artist       = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = June 26, 2007\n| recorded     = 2006\u20132007\n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Sony Pictures Studios]], [[Culver City, CA]]\n| genre        = [[21st-century classical music|Classical]], [[Film score]]\n| length       = 62:23\n| label        = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer     = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| chronology   = [[Pixar]] soundtrack\n| prev_title   = [[Cars (soundtrack)|Cars]]\n| prev_year    = 2006\n| next_title   = [[WALL-E (soundtrack)|WALL-E]]\n| next_year    = 2008\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n | type       = soundtrack\n | prev_title = [[Mission: Impossible III]]\n | prev_year  = 2006\n | title      = Ratatouille\n | year       = 2007\n | next_title = [[Cloverfield]]\n | next_year  = 2007\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=James Christopher Monger |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/ratatouille-original-soundtrack-mw0000573223 |title=Ratatouille [Original Soundtrack&#93; \u2013 Michael Giacchino &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |date=June 26, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|rev2=''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''\n|rev2score={{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=10111 |title=Empire's Ratatouille Soundtrack Review |work=Empire |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222151217/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=10111 |archivedate=February 22, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|rev3=[[SoundtrackNet]]\n|rev3score={{rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Andrew Granade |url=http://www.soundtrack.net/albums/database/?id=4506 |title=Ratatouille (2007) |publisher=Soundtrack |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n''Ratatouille'' is the second Pixar film to be scored by [[Michael Giacchino]] after ''The Incredibles''. It was also the second Pixar film not to be scored by [[Randy Newman]] or [[Thomas Newman]]. Giacchino had written two themes for Remy, one about his self with the rat colony and the other about his hopes and dreams. He also wrote a buddy theme for both Remy and Linguini that plays when they're together. In addition to the score, Giacchino wrote the main theme song, \"Le Festin\", about Remy and his wishes to be a chef. French artist [[Camille (singer)|Camille]] was hired to perform \"Le Festin\" after Giacchino listened to her music and realized she was perfect for the song; as a result, the song is sung in French in all versions of the film.<ref name=\"slashfilm1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.slashfilm.com/michael-giacchino-talks-music-pixar-d23-expo/ |title=Michael Giacchino Talks The Music Of Pixar [D23 Expo&#93; &#124; /Film |publisher=Slashfilm.com |date=September 2, 2011 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe music for ''Ratatouille'' gave Giacchino his first [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] as well as his first [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Score Soundtrack Album]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0315974/awards/ |title=Michael Giacchino IMDB}}</ref> Giacchino returned to Pixar to score their 2009 blockbuster ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''.<ref name=\"slashfilm1\"/>\n\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Le Festin\n| note1 = performed by [[Camille (singer)|Camille]]\n| length1 = 2:50\n| title2 = Welcome to Gusteau's\n| length2 = 0:38\n| title3 = This Is Me\n| length3 = 1:41\n| title4 = Granny Get Your Gun\n| length4 = 2:01\n| title5 = 100 Rat Dash\n| length5 = 1:47\n| title6 = Wall Rat\n| length6 = 2:41\n| title7 = Cast of Cooks\n| length7 = 1:41\n| title8 = A Real Gourmet Kitchen\n| length8 = 4:18\n| title9 = Souped Up\n| length9 = 0:50\n| title10 = Is It Soup Yet?\n| length10 = 1:16\n| title11 = A New Deal\n| length11 = 1:56\n| title12 = Remy Drives a Linguini\n| length12 = 2:26\n| title13 = Colette Shows Him le Ropes\n| length13 = 2:56\n| title14 = Special Order\n| length14 = 1:58\n| title15 = Kiss & Vinegar\n| length15 = 1:54\n| title16 = Losing Control\n| length16 = 2:04\n| title17 = Heist to See You\n| length17 = 1:45\n| title18 = The Paper Chase\n| length18 = 1:44\n| title19 = Remy's Revenge\n| length19 = 3:24\n| title20 = Abandoning Ship\n| length20 = 2:55\n| title21 = Dinner Rush\n| length21 = 5:00\n| title22 = Anyone Can Cook\n| length22 = 3:13\n| title23 = End Creditouilles\n| length23 = 9:16\n| title24 = Ratatouille Main Theme\n| length24 = 2:09\n}}\n\n==Release==\n\n''Ratatouille'' was originally going to be released in 2006; however, in December 2004, the date was changed to 2007. This happened because [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]/[[Pixar]] changed the release date of ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', from November 2005 to June 2006, thus pushing ''Ratatouille'' to 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4078711.stm  |title=Pixar-Disney delay Cars release |work=[[BBC News]] |date=December 8, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''Ratatouille''{{'}}s world premiere was on June 22, 2007, at Los Angeles' [[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theater]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/vstory/VR1117967629.html?categoryid=38 |title=Audiences in on 'Ratatouille' pack |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro}}</ref> The commercial release was one week later, with the short film ''[[Lifted (2006 film)|Lifted]]'' preceding ''Ratatouille'' in theaters. Earlier in the year, it had received an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"quint\">{{cite news|author=Eric Vespe|title=Quint orders a giant plate of RATATOUILLE and eats it up!!! |publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |date=June 9, 2007 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/32939 |accessdate=June 10, 2007}}</ref> A [[test screening]] of the film was shown at the Harkins Cine Capri Theater in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] on June 16, 2007, at which a Pixar representative was present to collect viewer feedback.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pixarplanet.com/blog/report-from-pixar-screening-of-ratatouille |title=Report from Pixar Screening of Ratatouille&nbsp;\u2014 Upcoming Pixar |publisher=Pixarplanet.com |accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> Disney CEO Bob Iger announced an upcoming theatrical re-release of the film in 3D at the Disney shareholders meeting in March 2014.<ref name=cartoon>{{cite news |url=http://blog.bcdb.com/incredibles-animated-sequel-6987/ |title=Incredibles Animated Sequel |first=Dave |last=Koch |publisher=[[Big Cartoon DataBase|Big Cartoon News]] |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=March 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140319172802/http://blog.bcdb.com/incredibles-animated-sequel-6987/ |archivedate=March 19, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe trailer for ''Ratatouille'' debuted with the release of its immediate predecessor, ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]''. It depicts an original scene where Remy is caught on the cheese trolley in the restaurant's dining area, sampling the cheese and barely escaping the establishment, intercut with separate scenes of the rat explaining directly to the audience why he is taking such risks. Similar to most of Pixar's teaser trailers, the scene was not present in the final film release.<ref name=\"yahoo1\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/video/ratatouille-trailer-185316448.html |title='Ratatouille' Theatrical Trailer |publisher=Yahoo! |date=April 15, 2013 |accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA second trailer was released on March 23, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Ratatouille Trailer Coming Friday |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=March 19, 2007 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=19432 |accessdate=March 19, 2007}}</ref> The Ratatouille ''Big Cheese Tour'' began on May 11, 2007, with cooking demonstrations and a film preview.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Desowitz|first1=Bill|title=Ratatouille to Kick Off With 'Big Cheese Tour'|url=http://www.awn.com/news/ratatouille-kick-big-cheese-tour|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=August 7, 2016|date=May 11, 2007}}</ref> Voice actor Lou Romano attended the San Francisco leg of the tour for autograph signings.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ratatouille Big Cheese Slide With Lou Romano |publisher=JustPressPlay.net |date=July 16, 2007 |url=http://www.justpressplay.net/movies/ratatouille/news/ratatouille-big-cheese-slide-with-lou-romano.html |accessdate=July 17, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235924/http://www.justpressplay.net/movies/ratatouille/news/ratatouille-big-cheese-slide-with-lou-romano.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Ratatouille-wine.jpg|right|thumb|The front label of the planned ''Ratatouille'' wine to have been promoted by Disney, Pixar, and Costco, and subsequently pulled for its use of a cartoon character]]\nDisney and Pixar were working to bring a French-produced ''Ratatouille''-branded wine to [[Costco]] stores in August 2007, but abandoned plans because of complaints from the California [[Wine Institute (California)|Wine Institute]], citing standards in labelling that restrict the use of cartoon characters to avoid attracting under-age drinkers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/la-fi-ratwine28jul28,0,7091322.story?coll=la-home-center | title=Disney backs out of wine promotion |last=Lifster |first=Marc |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate =August 1, 2007 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, in place of releasing a theatrical trailer, a commercial featuring Remy and Emile was released in cinemas before its release to discourage obtaining unlicensed copies of films.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bvimovies.com/spotlight/anti_piracy.html |title=Ratatouille's Remy fights movie piracy |publisher=The Film Factory |accessdate=December 23, 2007}}</ref> Also, in the United Kingdom, the main characters were used for a commercial for the [[Nissan Note]], with Remy and Emile watching an original commercial for it made for the \"Surprisingly Spacious\" ad campaign and also parodying it, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visit4info.com/details.cfm?adid=49783 |title=Nissan Note Exploding Cars It's Possible |publisher=Visit4Info |accessdate=December 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDisney/Pixar was concerned that audiences, particularly children, would not be familiar with the word \"ratatouille\" and its pronunciation. The title was, therefore, also spelled phonetically within trailers and on posters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deepfocusreview.com/Reviews/ratatouille.asp |title=''Ratatouille'' review |last=Eggert |first=Brian | date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 15, 2007 |publisher=DeepFocusReview.com}}</ref> For similar reasons, in the American release of the film, on-screen text in French was printed in English, such as the title of Gusteau's cookbook and the sign telling kitchen staff to wash their hands, though, in the British English release, these are rendered in French. In Canada, the film was released theatrically with text in English, but on DVD, the majority of the text (including Gusteau's will) was in French.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117967050.html?categoryid=2520&cs=1 | title=Pixar hopes auds find 'Ratatouille' tasty |last=Graser |first=Marc |date=June 15, 2007 |accessdate=October 15, 2007 |work=Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nDisney released ''Ratatouille'' on high-definition [[Blu-ray|Blu-ray Disc]] and DVD in North America on November 6, 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disney/Pixar/Disc_Announcements/Disney_Serves_Up_Ratatouille_on_Blu-ray_this_November/852 | title=Disney Serves Up 'Ratatouille' on Blu-ray this November |publisher=High Def Digest |date=August 10, 2007 |accessdate=August 20, 2007 }}</ref> A new animated short film featuring Remy and Emile entitled ''[[Your Friend the Rat]]'' was included as a special feature, in which the two rats attempt to entreat the viewer, a human, to welcome rats as their friends, demonstrating the benefits and misconceptions of rats towards humanity through several historical examples. The eleven-minute short uses 3D animation, 2D animation, live action and even stop-motion animation, a first for Pixar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?category=0&id=45050&type=0 |title=Rat DVD Has First Pixar 2-D Toon |author=Patrick Lee |date=October 30, 2007 |accessdate=October 30, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230070708/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?category=0&id=45050&type=0 |archivedate=December 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe disc also includes a CG short entitled ''[[Lifted (2006 film)|Lifted]]'', which screened before the film during its theatrical run. It depicts an adolescent [[extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] attempting to abduct a sleeping human. Throughout the sequence, he is graded by an adult extraterrestrial in a manner reminiscent of a [[driver's license|driver's licensing]] exam road test. The entire short contains no dialogue, which is typical of Pixar Shorts not based on existing properties.<ref name=\"pixarplanet1\">{{cite web |url=http://pixarplanet.com/blog/first-lifted-review |title=First Lifted Review&nbsp;\u2014 Upcoming Pixar |publisher=Pixarplanet.com |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Also included among the special features are deleted scenes, a featurette featuring Brad Bird discussing filmmaking and chef [[Thomas Keller]] discussing culinary creativity entitled \"Fine Food and Film\", and four [[Easter egg (media)|easter eggs]]. Although the Region 1 Blu-ray edition has a French audio track, the Region 1 DVD does not, except for some copies marked as for sale only in Canada.<ref name=\"blu-ray1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Ratatouille-Blu-ray/549/ |title=Ratatouille Blu-ray |publisher=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt was released on DVD on November 6, 2007, and earned 4,919,574 units (equivalent to {{USD|73,744,414}}) on its first week (November 6\u201311, 2007) during which it topped the DVD charts. In total it sold 12,531,266 units ({{USD|189,212,532}}) becoming the second-best-selling animated DVD of 2007, both in units sold and sales revenue, behind ''[[Happy Feet]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/annual/2007.php |title=Top-Selling DVDs of 2007 |publisher=the-numbers.com |accessdate=January 11, 2011}}</ref>  Ratatouille was released on [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|4K UHD Blu-ray]] on September 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ratatouille 4K Blu-ray|url=https://www.amazon.com/RATATOUILLE-Blu-ray-Patton-Oswalt/dp/B07T3JPPZN/ref=tmm_frk_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|work=Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|date=September 10, 2019|via=Amazon.com|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 96% approval rating with an average rating of 8.47/10 based on 249 reviews. The site's consensus reads: \"Fast-paced and stunningly animated, ''Ratatouille'' adds another delightfully entertaining entry\u2014and a rather unlikely hero\u2014to the Pixar canon.\"<ref>{{Rotten Tomatoes|ratatouille}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], another review aggregator website which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 top reviews from mainstream critics, calculated a score of 96 out of 100 based on 37 reviews,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/highscores.shtml |title=All-Time High Scores: The Best-Reviewed Movies |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609114144/http://www.metacritic.com/film/highscores.shtml |archivedate=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> the highest of any Pixar film<ref>{{cite web|title=Pixar Animation Studios' Scores|url=http://www.metacritic.com/company/pixar-animation-studios?filter-options=movies&num_items=30&sort_options=metascore|website=Metacritic|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref> and the twenty-first highest film rating on the site.<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Movies of All Time|url=http://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all|website=Metacritic|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called ''Ratatouille'' \"a nearly flawless piece of popular art, as well as one of the most persuasive portraits of an artist ever committed to film\"; echoing the character Anton Ego in the film, he ended his review with a simple \"thank you\" to the creators of the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2007/06/29/movies/29rata.html |title=Voil\u00e0! A Rat for All Seasonings |work=The New York Times |first=A. O. |last=Scott |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=January 15, 2008}}</ref> Wally Hammond of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' gave the film five out of five stars, saying \"A test for tiny tots, a mite nostalgic and as male-dominated as a modern kitchen it may be, but these are mere quibbles about this delightful addition to the Pixar pantheon.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Wally Hammond |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/ratatouille |title=Ratatouille |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |date=October 8, 2007 |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> Andrea Gronvall of the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"Brad Bird's second collaboration with Pixar is more ambitious and meditative than his Oscar-winning ''The Incredibles''.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ratatouille/reviews/?type=top_critics |title=Ratatouille Reviews |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B, saying \"''Ratatouille'' has the Pixar technical magic without, somehow, the full Pixar flavor. It's Brad Bird's genial dessert, not so much incredible as merely sweetly edible.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20044993,00.html |title=Ratatouille |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 6, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"What makes ''Ratatouille'' such a hilarious and heartfelt wonder is the way Bird contrives to let it sneak up on you. And get a load of that score from Michael Giacchino, a perfect complement to a delicious meal.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> [[James Berardinelli]] of ''[[ReelViews]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"For parents looking to spend time in a theater with their kids or adults who want something lighter and less testosterone-oriented than the usual summer fare, ''Ratatouille'' offers a savory main course.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/r/ratatouille.html |title=Reelviews Movie Reviews |publisher=Reelviews.net |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Christy Lemire of the [[Associated Press]] gave the film a positive review, saying \"''Ratatouille'' is free of the kind of gratuitous pop-culture references that plague so many movies of the genre; it tells a story, it's very much of our world but it never goes for the cheap, easy gag.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"The master chefs at Pixar have blended all the right ingredients\u2014abundant verbal and visual wit, genius slapstick timing, a soupcon of Gallic sophistication\u2014to produce a warm and irresistible concoction.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Justin Chang Chief Film Critic @JustinCChang |url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/ratatouille-2-1200558501/ |title=Ratatouille |work=Variety |date=June 18, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMichael Phillips of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"The film may be animated, and largely taken up with rats, but its pulse is gratifyingly human. And you have never seen a computer-animated feature with this sort of visual panache and detail.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips |first=Michael |url=http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-070629-movies-review-ratatouille,0,3953295.story |title=Metromix. Movie review: ''Ratatouille'' |publisher=Web.archive.org |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715125627/http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-070629-movies-review-ratatouille%2C0%2C3953295.story |archivedate=July 15, 2007}}</ref> Rafer Guzman of ''[[Newsday]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"So many computer-animated movies are brash, loud and popping with pop-culture comedy, but ''Ratatouille'' has the warm glow of a favorite book. The characters are more than the sum of their gigabyte-consuming parts \u2013 they feel handcrafted.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Roger Moore of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave the film three out of five stars, saying \"Has Pixar lost its magic recipe? ''Ratatouille'' is filled with fairly generic animated imagery, a few modest chases, a couple of good gags, not a lot of laughs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-06-29/entertainment/RATATOUILLE_1_remy-linguini-rat |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206161721/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-06-29/entertainment/RATATOUILLE_1_remy-linguini-rat |archivedate =February 6, 2014 |title=Rats: You can't carry a 'toon by blathering on about food |work=Orlando Sentinel |first=Roger |last=Moore |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Scott Foundas of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"Bird has taken the raw ingredients of an anthropomorphic-animal kiddie matinee and whipped them into a heady brew about nothing less than the principles of artistic creation.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Olsen |first=Mark |url=http://www.laweekly.com/film/ratatouille-rat-can-cook-2149508 |title=Ratatouille: Rat Can Cook |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> Colin Covert of the ''[[Star Tribune]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"It's not just the computer animation that is vibrantly three-dimensional. It's also the well-rounded characters\u2026 I defy you to name another animated film so overflowing with superfluous beauty.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Steven Rea of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"With ''Ratatouille'', Bird once again delivers not just a great, witty story, but dazzling visuals as well.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Rea |first=Steven |url=http://articles.philly.com/2007-06-29/entertainment/24994660_1_remy-sous-chef-auguste-gusteau |title=You'll smell a ... terrific 'toon, starring a rat  |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> Bill Muller of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' gave the film four-and-a-half stars out of five, saying \"Like the burbling soup that plays a key part in ''Ratatouille'', the movie is a delectable blend of ingredients that tickles the palette and leaves you hungry for more.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/>\n\n[[File:Bradbird.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Brad Bird]] with his second [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]]]]\nRene Rodriguez of the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"''Ratatouille'' is the most straightforward and formulaic picture to date from Pixar Animation Studios, but it is also among the most enchanting and touching.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ae.miami.com/entertainment/ui/miami/movie.html?id=898393&reviewId=22542 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070623044747/http://ae.miami.com/entertainment/ui/miami/movie.html?id=898393&reviewId=22542 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 23, 2007 |title=Movie: Ratatouille |date=December 1, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Jack Mathews of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"The Pixar magic continues with Brad Bird's ''Ratatouille'', a gorgeous, wonderfully inventive computer-animated comedy.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/rat-catch-article-1.219691 |title=A rat to catch! |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 }}</ref> Stephen Whitty of the ''[[Newark Star-Ledger]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"Fresh family fun. Although there are those slightly noxious images of rodents scampering around a kitchen, the movie doesn't stoop to kid-pandering jokes based on backtalk and bodily gases.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> David Ansen of ''[[Newsweek]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"A film as rich as a sauce b\u00e9arnaise, as refreshing as a raspberry sorbet, and a lot less predictable than the damn food metaphors and adjectives all us critics will churn out to describe it. OK, one more and then I'll be done: it's yummy.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ansen |first=David |url=http://www.newsweek.com/ansen-ratatouille-102579 |title=Ansen on 'Ratatouille' |work=Newsweek |date=June 28, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Peter Hartlaub of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"''Ratatouille'' never overwhelms, even though it's stocked with action, romance, historical content, family drama and serious statements about the creation of art.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Hartlaub, Chronicle Pop Culture Critic |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Ratatouille-is-a-feast-for-the-eyes-2583888.php |title=\"Ratatouille\" is a feast for the eyes |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=June 28, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Richard Corliss of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"From the moment Remy enters, crashing, to the final happy fadeout, ''Ratatouille'' parades the brio and depth that set Pixar apart from and above other animation studios.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Corliss |first=Richard |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1630548,00.html |title=Savoring Pixar's Ratatouille |work=TIME |date=June 7, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"A lot of animated movies have inspired sequels, notably ''[[Shrek]]'', but Brad Bird's ''Ratatouille'' is the first one that made me positively desire one.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Ebert |first=Roger |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/ratatouille-2007 |title=Ratatouille Movie Review & Film Summary (2007) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=August 30, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Peter Howell of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"Had Bird gone the safe route, he would have robbed us of a great new cartoon figure in Remy, who like the rest of the film is rendered with animation that is at once fanciful and life-like. It's also my pick for Pixar's best.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2007/06/29/feast_your_eyes.html |title=Feast your eyes |work=Toronto Star |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJoe Morgenstern of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"The characters are irresistible, the animation is astonishing and the film, a fantasy version of a foodie rhapsody, sustains a level of joyous invention that hasn't been seen in family entertainment since ''The Incredibles''.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Morgenstern |first=Joe |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB118307125242752135?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB118307125242752135.html |title=Pixar Cooks With Joy, Inventiveness In 'Ratatouille' |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Kenneth Turan of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film four-and-a-half stars out of five, saying \"Brad Bird's ''Ratatouille'' is so audacious you have to fall in love with its unlikely hero.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jun/29/entertainment/et-ratatouille29 |title=This is no dirty rat&nbsp;|work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Kenneth |last=Turan}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"''Ratatouille'' is delicious fun sure to be savored by audiences of all ages for its sumptuous visuals, clever wit and irresistibly inspiring tale.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Miriam Di Nunzio of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"''Ratatouille'' will make you wonder why animation needs to hide behind the mantle of 'it's for children, but grownups will like it, too.' This one's for Mom and Dad, and yep, the kids will like it, too.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Chicago Sun-Times |url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/447829,CST-FTR-rat29.article |title=A vermin in Paris finds his inner foodie |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701151410/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/447829%2CCST-FTR-rat29.article |archivedate=July 1, 2007}}</ref> Michael Booth of ''[[The Denver Post]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"Writer and director Brad Bird keeps ''Ratatouille'' moving without resorting to the cute animal jokes or pop-culture wisecracking that ruined so many other recent animated films.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/movies/ci_6245556 |title=Oui! A rich foodie treat, with a great view |work=The Denver Post |date=June 28, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Michael |last=Booth}}</ref> Tom Long of ''[[The Detroit News]]'' gave the film an A, saying \"''Ratatouille'' has the technical genius, emotional core and storytelling audacity to lift it into the ranks of [the best] Pixar films, the cr\u00e8me de la cr\u00e8me of modern animation.\" Liam Lacey of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"No sketchy backgrounds here\u2014''Ratatouille''{{'}}s scenes feel like deep-focus camera shots. The textures, from the gleam of copper pans to the cobblestone streets, are almost palpable.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Desson Thomson of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"''Ratatouille'' doesn't center on the over-familiar surfaces of contemporary life. It harks back to Disney's older era when cartoons seemed part of a more elegant world with less edgy characters.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/28/AR2007062802484.html |title='Ratatouille': A Classic Recipe |work=The Washington Post |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Desson |last=Thomson}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIn its opening weekend in North America, ''Ratatouille'' opened in 3,940 theaters and debuted at number one with $47 million,<ref>{{cite news |author=Pamela McClintock |title=Audiences chow down on \"Ratatouille\" |work=Variety | date=July 1, 2007 | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117967918.html?categoryid=13&cs=1}}</ref> the lowest Pixar opening since ''[[A Bug's Life]]''. However, in France, where the film is set, the film broke the record for the biggest debut for an animated film.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ratatouille Breaks French Record |publisher=Starpulse |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/08/11/ratatouille_breaks_french_record |accessdate=August 13, 2007 |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the film debuted at number one with sales over \u00a34 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukfilmcouncil.org.uk/cinemagoing/boxoffice/?p=D4A1577818d4b19146vpK3480F76&skip= |title=UK Film Box Office: Oct. 12&nbsp;\u2013 Oct. 14 |publisher=[[UK Film Council]] |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102041654/http://www.ukfilmcouncil.org.uk/cinemagoing/boxoffice/?p=D4A1577818d4b19146vpK3480F76&skip= <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=November 2, 2007}}</ref> The film has grossed $206.4 million in the United States and Canada and a total of $620.7 million worldwide, making it the seventh-highest-grossing [[Pixar]] film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/series/Pixar.php |title=Pixar Box Office History |accessdate=July 31, 2010 |publisher=The Numbers}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Ratatouille}}\n''Ratatouille'' won the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]] at the [[80th Academy Awards]] and was nominated for four others: [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], losing to ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]'', ''[[The Bourne Ultimatum (film)|The Bourne Ultimatum]]'' (for both Best Sound Editing and Best Sound Mixing), and ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'', respectively.<ref name=\"academy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |title=Winners and Nominees&nbsp;\u2013 80th Academy Awards |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=January 6, 2009 |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012045551/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |archivedate=October 12, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"oscars2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |title=Nominees & Winners of the 2008 (80th) Academy Awards &#124; Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |date=August 24, 2012 |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012045551/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |archivedate=October 12, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> At the time, the film held the record for the greatest number of Oscar nominations for a computer animated feature film, breaking the previous record held by ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'', ''[[Finding Nemo]]'', and ''[[The Incredibles]]'' at four nominations, but tied with ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'' for any animated film. In 2008, ''[[WALL-E]]'' surpassed that record with six nominations. As of 2013, ''Ratatouille'' is tied with ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 3]]'' for an animated film with the second-greatest number of Oscar nominations. ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' still holds the record for most Oscar nominations (also 6) for an animated feature film.<ref name=\"oscars2000\"/>\n\nFurthermore, ''Ratatouille'' was nominated for 13 [[Annie Award]]s including twice in the Best Animated Effects, where it lost to ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'', and three times in the Best Voice Acting in an Animated Feature Production for Janeane Garofalo, Ian Holm, and Patton Oswalt, where Ian Holm won the award.<ref name=\"annie\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/35thwinners.html |title=Annie Awards 2007 nominations |publisher=[[ASIFA-Hollywood|International Animated Film Association]] |accessdate=March 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204082048/http://annieawards.org/35thwinners.html |archivedate=December 4, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref> It won the Best Animated Feature Award from multiple associations including the [[Chicago Film Critics Association|Chicago Film Critics]],<ref name=\"chicago\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48:Chicago%20Film%20Critics%20Awards&Itemid=58 |title=Chicago Film Critics Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1998-07 |publisher=Chicago Film Critics Association |accessdate=March 9, 2009}}</ref> the [[National Board of Review]],<ref name=\"national\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/past.cfm?year=2007 |title=Awards for 2007 |publisher=National Board of Review |accessdate=March 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211184324/http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/past.cfm?year=2007 |archivedate=December 11, 2007}}</ref> the Annie Awards,<ref name=\"annie\"/> the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association|Broadcast Film Critics]],<ref name=\"broadcast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfca.org/ccawards/2007.php |title=The 13th Critics Choice Awards winners and nominees |publisher=Broadcast Film Critics Association |accessdate=March 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120530075853/http://www.bfca.org/ccawards/2007.php |archivedate=May 30, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> the [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy of Film and Television (BAFTA)]], and the [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]].<ref name=\"globes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 |title=Hollywood Foreign Press Association 2008 Golden Globe Awards for the year ended December 31, 2007 |publisher=HFPA |date=December 13, 2007 |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215072618/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=December 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Plagiarized film==\n{{see also|Mockbuster}}\n[[If (magazine)|''If'' magazine]] described ''[[Ratatoing]]'', a 2007 [[Brazil]]ian [[computer animation|computer graphics]] cartoon by [[V\u00eddeo Brinquedo]], as a \"[[ripoff]]\" of ''Ratatouille''.<ref>\"[http://www.ifmagazine.com/review.asp?article=2247 Clip of the Week: RATATOING&nbsp;\u2013 BRAZIL RIPOFF OF RATATOUILLE]\", ''[[If (magazine)|If]]'' {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123055130/http://www.ifmagazine.com/review.asp?article=2247 |date=January 23, 2008 }}</ref> Marco Aur\u00e9lio Can\u00f4nico of the Brazilian newspaper, ''[[Folha de S.Paulo]]'' described ''Ratatoing'' as a derivative of ''Ratatouille''. Can\u00f4nico discussed whether ''Ratatoing'' was similar enough to ''Ratatouille'' to warrant a lawsuit for copyright violation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429215943/http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |title=V\u00eddeo Brinquedo faz sucesso com desenhos como \"Os Carrinhos\" e \"Ratatoing\" |language=Portuguese |work=Folha de S.Paulo |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (Brazil)|Ministry of Culture]] (Brazil) |quote=\"These descriptions bring to mind ''Cars'' and ''Ratatouille'', the latest two feature films by North American giant Pixar, a part of Disney\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429215943/http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |archivedate=April 29, 2008| accessdate= October 6, 2019}}</ref>  The [[Ministry of Culture (Brazil)|Brazilian Ministry of Culture]] posted Marco Aur\u00e9lio Can\u00f4nico's article on its website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |title=V\u00eddeo Brinquedo faz sucesso com desenhos como \"Os Carrinhos\" e \"Ratatoing\" |language=Portuguese |work=Folha de S.Paulo |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (Brazil)|Ministry of Culture]] (Brazil) |quote=\"These descriptions bring to mind ''Cars'' and ''Ratatouille'', the latest two feature films by North American giant Pixar, a part of Disney\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429215943/http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |archivedate=April 29, 2008}}</ref> To date no sources have been found to indicate that Pixar took legal action.\n\n==Video game==\n{{Main|Ratatouille (video game)}}\nThe primary video game adaptation of the film, titled ''[[Ratatouille (video game)|Ratatouille]]'', was released for all major consoles and handhelds in 2007. A [[Nintendo DS]] exclusive game, titled ''[[Ratatouille: Food Frenzy]]'', was released in October 2007. ''Ratatouille'' is also among the films represented in ''[[Kinect Rush: A Disney-Pixar Adventure]]'', released in March 2012 for [[Xbox 360]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Narcisse |first=Evan |title=Pixar Teams Up With Microsoft For Kinect Rush |url=http://kotaku.com/5866341/pixar-teams-up-with-microsoft-for-kinect-rush/ |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |newspaper=Kotaku |date=December 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe video game based on the movie was released in 2007 for [[Xbox 360]], [[Wii]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[GameCube]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[PlayStation Portable]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]], and [[mobile phone]]s.  A [[PlayStation 3]] version was released on October 23, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/disneypixar-ratatouille|title=Disney/Pixar Ratatouille|website=Metacritic|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> The other versions, however were all released on June 26, 2007.\n\nRemy is featured in the video game ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''. He appears as the head chef for [[Scrooge McDuck|Scrooge McDuck's]] bistro and participates with [[Sora (Kingdom Hearts)|Sora]] in cooking minigames. He is addressed only as \"Little Chef\" in the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/11/17447614/kingdom-hearts-3-gameplay-e3-2018-ratatouille |title=Kingdom Hearts 3 trailer features a new, lovable Pixar character |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media, Inc.]]}}</ref>\n\n==Theme park attraction==\n{{Main|Ratatouille: L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de R\u00e9my}}\nA Disney theme park attraction based on the film has been constructed in [[Walt Disney Studios Park]], [[Disneyland Paris]]. [[Ratatouille: L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de R\u00e9my|''Ratatouille'': L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de R\u00e9my]] is based upon scenes from the film and uses trackless ride technology. In the attraction, riders \"shrink down to the size of a rat\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dlptoday.com/news/walt-disney-studios-park/toon-studio/ratatouille-dark-ride/ |title=Ratatouille: The Adventure&nbsp;\u2013 L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de Remy |work=DLP Today |accessdate=October 9, 2014}}</ref>\nAt the 2017 D23 Expo, Disney announced a similar, ''Ratatouille''-based attraction would be built at the [[France Pavilion at Epcot|France Pavilion]] in [[Epcot|Epcot's]] World Showcase by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/15/business/media/disney-epcot-theme-parks.html|title=Disney Vows to Give Epcot a Magical, Long-Overdue Makeover|first=Brooks|last=Barnes|date=July 15, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Price |first=David |year=2008 |title=The Pixar Touch: The Making of a Company |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |isbn=978-0-307-26575-3 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780307265753 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Ratatouille}}\n{{Commons category|Ratatouille (film)}}\n* {{Official website|http://movies.disney.com/ratatouille}}\n* {{IMDb title|0382932}}\n* {{tcmdb title|641780}}\n* {{Bcdb title|62177}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|ratatouille}}\n* {{Metacritic film|ratatouille}}\n* {{Mojo title|ratatouille}}\n\n{{Ratatouille}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{Brad Bird}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of accolades received by Ratatouille|Awards for ''Ratatouille'']]\n|list=\n{{Academy Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Annie Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Animated Motion Picture}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Animated or Mixed Media Feature Film}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Animated Film}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Animation|Film|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Ratatouille (film)| ]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2007 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about animals]]\n[[Category:Animated films about friendship]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature BAFTA winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Broadcast Film Critics Association Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Film Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Cooking films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about chefs]]\n[[Category:Films about food and drink]]\n[[Category:Films about rats]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Brad Bird]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in restaurants]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Brad Bird]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about rats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ratatouille\n| image          = RatatouillePoster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| border         = yes\n| alt            = Remy, a rat, smiles nervously as he clings onto a piece of cheese while he is pinned to a door by sharp knives and forks. The film's tagline, \"He's dying to become a chef\", is displayed along the top. A logo with the film's title and pronunciation is shown at the bottom, with the dot on the 'i' in \"Ratatouille\" doubling as a rat's nose with whiskers and a chef's toque.\n| director       = [[Brad Bird]]\n| producer       = [[Brad Lewis]]\n| screenplay     = Brad Bird\n| story          = {{unbulleted list|[[Jan Pinkava]]|Jim Capobianco|Brad Bird}}\n| music          = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Patton Oswalt]]\n* [[Ian Holm]]\n* [[Lou Romano]]\n* [[Janeane Garofalo]]\n* [[Brad Garrett]]\n* [[Peter O'Toole]]\n* [[Brian Dennehy]]\n* [[Peter Sohn]]\n* [[Will Arnett]]\n}}\n| cinematography = {{unbulleted list|[[Sharon Calahan]]|Robert Anderson}}\n| editing        = {{unbulleted list|[[Darren T. Holmes]]|Stan Webb}}\n| studio         = {{unbulleted list|[[Walt Disney Pictures]]|[[Pixar Animation Studios]]}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures Distribution]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|6|22|[[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theatre]]|2007|6|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 111 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $150&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Cieply|title=It's Not a Sequel, but It Might Seem Like One After the Ads|work=The New York Times|date=April 24, 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/24/movies/24orig.html}}</ref>\n| gross          = $620.7&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ratatouille.htm |title=Ratatouille (2007) |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 4, 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Ratatouille''''' is a 2007 American [[computer-animated]] [[comedy film]] produced by [[Pixar]] and released by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. It was the eighth film produced by [[Pixar]], and was written and directed by [[Brad Bird]], who took over from [[Jan Pinkava]] in 2005, and produced by [[Brad Lewis]], from an original idea from Pinkava and Jim Capobianco. The title refers to the French dish [[ratatouille]], which is served at the end of the film and also references the animal type of the main character, a rat. The plot follows a [[rat]] named Remy, who dreams of becoming a chef and tries to achieve his goal by forming an alliance with a Parisian restaurant's garbage boy. \n\nThe film stars the voices of [[Patton Oswalt]] as Remy, an [[anthropomorphic]] [[rat]] who is interested in cooking; [[Lou Romano]] as Alfredo Linguini, a young garbage boy who befriends Remy; [[Ian Holm]] as Skinner, the head chef of Auguste Gusteau's restaurant; [[Janeane Garofalo]] as Colette Tatou, a [[r\u00f4tisseur]] at Gusteau's restaurant and the staff's only female chef; [[Peter O'Toole]] as Anton Ego, a restaurant critic; [[Brian Dennehy]] as Django,  Remy's father and leader of his clan; [[Peter Sohn]] as Emile, Remy's older brother; and [[Brad Garrett]] as Auguste Gusteau, a recently deceased chef.\n\nThe development of ''Ratatouille'' began in 2000 when Pinkava wrote the original concepts of the film. In 2005, following Pinkava's departure from Pixar, Bird was approached to direct the film and revise the story. Bird and some of the film's crew members also visited Paris for inspiration. To create the food animation used in the film, the crew consulted chefs from both France and the United States. Lewis interned at [[Thomas Keller]]'s [[The French Laundry]] restaurant, where Keller developed the [[confit byaldi]], a dish used in the film. [[Michael Giacchino]] composed the Paris-inspired music for the film.\n\n''Ratatouille'' premiered on June 22, 2007, at the [[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], with its general release June 29, 2007, in the United States. The film grossed  $620.7 million and was a box office success. It received critical acclaim for Giacchino's score, voice acting, writing, and the animation. The film won the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]] and was nominated for four more, including [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]. It was later voted one of the 100 greatest motion pictures of the 21st century by a [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century|2016 poll of international critics]] conducted by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=The 21st Century's 100 greatest films |publisher=BBC |date=August 23, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nRemy is a highly intelligent and idealistic young rat with unusually acute senses of taste and smell, who dreams of becoming a chef like his idol, the late Auguste Gusteau. However, the rest of his colony, including his brother Emile and his father Django, are interested in food only for sustenance. One day, when the colony is forced to flee their home because of Remy and Emile's wild encounter with the homeowner whose ceiling housed their colony, Remy is separated from the clan and eventually finds himself above the kitchen of Gusteau's Restaurant in Paris.\n\nWhen Remy observes a young garbage boy named Alfredo Linguini attempt to fix a soup he has spilled, he recognizes that Linguini is unintentionally ruining it and fixes his mistakes. Linguini catches him in the act, but does not reveal him to Skinner, Gusteau's former [[sous-chef]] and new owner of the restaurant. Skinner confronts Linguini for tampering with the soup, but when the soup is accidentally served to a critic and proves to be a success, Colette Tatou, the staff's only female chef, convinces Skinner to retain Linguini. Skinner spots Remy trying to escape, and orders Linguini to kill the rat, but Linguini decides to keep Remy instead. \n\nWhen Linguini is ordered to replicate the soup, he is helped by Remy. Skinner, having tried the soup, decides to retain Linguini. Back in Linguini's apartment the two learn to communicate and devise a plan:  Remy hides under Linguini's [[toque]] at the restaurant and guides his movements like a [[marionette]] by pulling on his hair. Skinner orders Colette to teach Linguini to be a cook.\n\nRemy witnesses Skinner's discovery that Linguini is Gusteau's illegitimate son and rightful owner of the restaurant, and gives the evidence to Linguini, who forces Skinner out. The restaurant thrives as Remy's recipes become popular, though as Linguini and Colette develop a relationship, Remy begins to feel left out. He reunites with Emile and the clan, but is rejected by Django over his admiration for humans.\n\nThe dour world-renowned food critic Anton Ego, whose negative review had indirectly led to Gusteau's death, announces he will once again dine at the restaurant. After an argument with Linguini, Remy leads his clan to raid the restaurant's pantries in revenge, but Linguini drives them out. Remy is captured by Skinner, who intends to use his talents to create a line of frozen food products, but is promptly freed by Django and Emile. Linguini apologizes to Remy, having been unable to cook without him, and reveals the truth to his staff, but they all leave, heartbroken and in disbelief. Colette returns after recalling Gusteau's motto, \"Anyone can cook.\"\n\nImpressed by Remy's determination, Django and the clan offer to help, and cook under Remy's direction while Linguini waits tables. Skinner attempts to interfere, but is bound, gagged, and banished from the restaurant. Remy creates a variation on [[ratatouille]] which reminds Ego of his mother's cooking. Humbled and delighted by the dish, Ego asks to meet the chef, so Linguini and Colette wait until the other diners have left before introducing Remy. Ego is stunned and writes a glowing review, saying how he now understands Gusteau's famous motto, and indirectly calling Remy \"nothing less than the finest chef in France.\"\n\nDespite the review, the restaurant is shut down due to the presence of the rats, causing Ego to lose his job and credibility as a critic. However, he now funds and frequents a popular new bistro, ''La Ratatouille,'' run by Remy, Linguini, and Colette as the rat colony settles into their new home in the bistro's attic.\n\n==Voice cast==\n<!-- This section is meant to contain introductions only. It is not meant to include major plot elements. Please refrain from including such information -->\n{{div col|colwidth=}}\n\n*[[Patton Oswalt]] as Remy, a rat with heightened senses of taste and smell, enabling a talent and desire for cooking. Director Brad Bird chose Oswalt after hearing his food-related comedy routine.<ref name=\"moryvisit\">{{cite news |author=Drew McWeeny |title=Moriarty Visits Pixar To Chat With Brad Bird And Patton Oswalt About RATATOUILLE! |publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |date=May 21, 2007 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/32729 |accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Ian Holm]] as Chef Skinner, a diminutive chef and the owner of Auguste Gusteau's restaurant. Since Gusteau's death, Skinner has used the Gusteau name to market a line of cheap microwaveable meals. Skinner's behavior, diminutive size, and [[body language]] are loosely based on [[Louis de Fun\u00e8s]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.telemoustique.be/cps/rde/xchg/tm/hs.xsl/magazine_ratatouille.html?archive_numero=4254 |title=Ratatouille, le film |publisher=Telemoustique |date=August 8, 2007 |language=French|accessdate=December 22, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071211061319/http://www.telemoustique.be/cps/rde/xchg/tm/hs.xsl/magazine_ratatouille.html?archive_numero=4254 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = December 11, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Lou Romano]] as Alfredo Linguini, the son of Auguste Gusteau and Renata Linguini, and a hapless garbage boy who befriends Remy. He is named after [[Alfredo Ferrari]], the son of Italian automaker [[Enzo Ferrari]].\n*[[Janeane Garofalo]] as Colette Tatou, Gusteau's ''[[chef de partie|r\u00f4tisseur]]''. She is inspired by French chef [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Darroze]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Molly|last2=Gavard|first2=Corinne|title=A Taste of Whimsy Wows the French|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/13/AR2007081300990.html|accessdate=November 16, 2014|work=The Washington Post|date=August 14, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Brad Garrett]] as Auguste Gusteau, France's most famous chef, who died a broken heart following a negative review by Anton Ego. Many reviewers believe that Gusteau is inspired by real-life chef [[Bernard Loiseau]], who committed suicide after media speculation that his flagship restaurant, La C\u00f4te d'Or, was going to be downgraded from three [[Michelin Guide|Michelin stars]] to two.<ref>{{cite news |author=Molly Moore and Corinne Gavard |title=A Taste of Whimsy Wows the French |work=The Washington Post |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/13/AR2007081300990.html |accessdate=August 14, 2007 | date=August 14, 2007}}</ref> La&nbsp;C\u00f4te d'Or was one of the restaurants visited by Brad Bird and others in France.<ref name=\"parlez\"/>\n*[[Peter O'Toole]] as Anton Ego, a restaurant critic whose negative review led to Gusteau's five-star restaurant being downgraded to four. His appearance was modeled after [[Louis Jouvet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lesoir.be/culture/cinema/louis-de-funes-louis-jouvet-2007-08-01-542527.shtml |title=Louis De Fun\u00e8s, Louis Jouvet, Charles De Gaulle... Le jour de gloire est arriv\u00e9. Et au diable les \" freedom fries \" ! |publisher=Lesoir.be |language=French |date=August 1, 2007 |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102035303/http://www.lesoir.be/culture/cinema/louis-de-funes-louis-jouvet-2007-08-01-542527.shtml |archivedate=January 2, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Brian Dennehy]] as Django,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.scribd.com/document/6695691/Ratatouille-Script|title=Ratatouille Script|website=Scribd|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>  Remy and Emile's father, and the leader of the rats.\n*[[Peter Sohn]] as Emile, Remy's gluttonous older brother.\n*[[Will Arnett]] as Horst, Skinner's German [[sous chef]].\n*Julius Callahan as Lalo, Gusteau's ''[[saucier]]'' and ''poissonnier''. Callahan also voices Fran\u00e7ois, the advertising executive handling the marketing of Gusteau's microwaveable products.\n*[[James Remar]] as Larousse, Gusteau's ''chef [[garde manger]]''.\n*[[John Ratzenberger]] as Mustafa, Gusteau's ''chef de salle''.\n*[[Teddy Newton]] as Talon Labarthe, Skinner's lawyer.\n*Tony Fucile as Pompidou, Gusteau's ''[[patissier]]''. Fucile also voices Nadar Lessard, a [[health inspector]] employed by Skinner.\n*[[Jake Steinfeld]] as Git, a former lab rat and member of Django's colony.\n*[[Brad Bird]] as Ambrister Minion, Anton Ego's butler.\n*[[St\u00e9phane Roux (actor)|St\u00e9phane Roux]] as the narrator of the cooking channel.\n*[[Thomas Keller]], the restaurateur, as a dining patron who asks \"what's new\".<ref name=\"sfcarticle\"/> In other-language versions, this role is also voiced by a chef.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Jan Pinkava]] came up with the concept in 2000, creating the original design, sets and characters and core storyline, but he was never formally named the director of the film.<ref>{{cite web | author = Leo N. Holzer | title = Pixar cooks up a story | work = The Reporter | date = June 29, 2007 | url = http://www.thereporter.com/billboard/ci_6260970 | accessdate = June 29, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070702164407/http://www.thereporter.com/billboard/ci_6260970# | archive-date = July 2, 2007 | url-status=dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> By 2004, Pixar added [[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]] as a co-director and was given exclusive control of the story.{{sfn|Price|2008|p=249}} Lacking confidence in the story development,<ref>{{cite news|author=Steve Daly |title=Brad Bird cooks up \"Ratatouille\" |work=Entertainment Weekly |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20166944_20166964_20043277_2,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506073932/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C20166944_20166964_20043277_2%2C00.html |archivedate=May 6, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Incredibles]]'' director [[Brad Bird]] was approached by Pixar management to direct the film, taking over Pinkava's role in 2005 while Peterson left the film to work on ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''.<ref name=\"early taste\">{{cite news | author=Bill Desowitz | title = Brad Bird Offers an Early Taste of Ratatouille | publisher=Animation World Magazine | date = April 25, 2007 | url = https://www.awn.com/animationworld/brad-bird-offers-early-taste-ratatouille | accessdate=May 22, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Jim Hill | title = Why For did Disney struggle to come up with a marketing campaign for Pixar's latest picture? Because the Mouse wasn't originally supposed to release \"Ratatouille\" | publisher=Jim Hill Media | date = June 28, 2007 | url = http://jimhillmedia.com/blogs/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/28/toon-thursday-why-did-disney-struggle-to-come-up-with-a-ratatouille-marketing-campaign-because-the-mouse-wasn-t-supposed-to-release-this-particular-pixar-film.aspx | accessdate =July 1, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/26/AR2007062601251.html | title = Pixar Perfectionists Cook `Ratatouille' |work=The Washington Post | date = June 26, 2007 | accessdate =January 15, 2008 | first = David | last = Germain }}</ref>{{sfn|Price|2008|p=250}} Bird was attracted to the film because of the outlandishness of the concept and the conflict that drove it: that rats feared kitchens, yet a rat wanted to work in one.<ref name=\"moryvisit\"/> Bird was also delighted that the film could be made a highly [[physical comedy]],<ref name=\"early taste\"/> with the character of Linguini providing endless fun for the animators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Linguini a la Carte |publisher=Yahoo! |date=May 22, 2007 |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |accessdate=May 23, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526103543/http://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |archivedate=May 26, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Bird rewrote the story, with a change in emphasis. He killed off Gusteau, gave larger roles to Skinner and Colette,<ref>{{cite news | author=Helen O'Hara | title = First Look: Ratatouille | work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] | page = 62 | date = June 28, 2007}}</ref> and also changed the appearance of the rats to be less [[anthropomorphic]].<ref name=\"ignedit\">{{cite web | author = Scott Collura & Eric Moro | title = Edit Bay Visit: Ratatouille | website = IGN | date = April 25, 2007 | url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/783/783392p1.html | accessdate = May 22, 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091109104953/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/783/783392p1.html | archivedate = November 9, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBecause ''Ratatouille'' is intended to be a romantic, lush vision of Paris, giving it an identity distinct from previous Pixar films,<ref name=\"early taste\"/> director Brad Bird, producer Brad Lewis and some of the crew spent a week in the city to properly understand its environment, taking a motorcycle tour and eating at five top restaurants.<ref name=\"parlez\">{{cite web|title=Parlez-vous Francais |publisher=Yahoo! |date=May 22, 2007 |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |accessdate=May 23, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526103543/http://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Ratatouille/1808490293/trailers/8/381 |archivedate=May 26, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> [[Peter Dinklage]] was offered the role of Skinner, but he turned down the role. [[Ian Holm]] was cast as the character since Bird saw him on [[The Lord of the Rings (film trilogy)|''The Lord of the Rings'' trilogy]]. There are also many water-based sequences in the film, one of which is set in the sewers and is more complex than the [[blue whale]] scene in ''[[Finding Nemo]]''. One scene has Linguini wet after jumping into the [[Seine]] to fetch Remy. A Pixar employee (Shade/Paint department coordinator Kesten Migdal) jumped into Pixar's swimming pool wearing a chef's uniform and apron to see which parts of the suit stuck to his body and which became translucent from water absorption.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Technical Ingredients |publisher=Disney Pictures | url=http://disney.go.com/disneypictures/ratatouille/main.html |accessdate=May 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Confit byaldi 1.jpg|thumb|The film's take on the traditional ratatouille dish was designed by gourmet chef Thomas Keller and later came to be known as [[confit byaldi]].]]\nA challenge for the filmmakers was creating computer-generated images of food that would appear delicious. Gourmet chefs in both the U.S. and France were consulted,<ref name=\"ignedit\"/> and animators attended cooking classes at [[San Francisco Bay Area|San Francisco-area]] culinary schools to understand the workings of a [[commercial kitchen]].<ref name=\"sfcarticle\">{{cite news | accessdate=June 29, 2007 | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/06/28/MNGGIQNA7M1.DTL |work=San Francisco Chronicle | date=June 28, 2007 | author=Stacy Finz | title=Bay Area flavors food tale: For its new film 'Ratatouille,' Pixar explored our obsession with cuisine}}</ref> Sets/Layout department manager Michael Warch, a culinary-academy-trained professional chef before working at Pixar, helped teach and consult animators as they worked. He also prepared dishes used by the Art, Shade/Paint, Effects and Sets Modeling departments.<ref name=\"cook 101\">{{cite web | title=Cooking 101 | publisher=Disney Pictures |url=http://disney.go.com/disneypictures/ratatouille/main.html |accessdate=May 23, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"nytfood\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/13/dining/13rata.html?ex=1339387200&en=988ed2df8b9bcdb4&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss |author=Kim Severson |date=June 13, 2007| title=A Rat With a Whisk and a Dream |accessdate=June 30, 2007 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> Renowned chef [[Thomas Keller]] allowed producer Brad Lewis to intern in his [[French Laundry]] kitchen. For the film's [[Climax (narrative)|climax]], Keller designed a fancy, layered version of the title dish for the rat characters to cook, which he called \"[[confit byaldi]]\" in honor of the [[Imam bayildi|original Turkish name]].<ref name=\"sfcarticle\"/> The same [[Subsurface scattering|sub-surface light scattering]] technique that was used on the skin in ''[[The Incredibles]]'' was used on fruits and vegetables,<ref name=\"animated edit\"/> while new programs gave an organic texture and movement to the food.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cooking Up CG Food |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=May 24, 2007 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=20608 |accessdate=May 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526042435/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=20608 |archivedate=May 26, 2007 }}</ref> Completing the illusion were music, dialogue, and [[abstract imagery]] representing the characters' mental sensations while appreciating food. The visual flavor [[metaphor]]s were created by animator [[Michel Gagn\u00e9]] inspired by the work of [[Oscar Fischinger]] and [[Norman McLaren]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gagneint.com/Final%20site/Animation/Pixar/Ratatouille.htm |author=Michel Gagn\u00e9|publisher=Gagne International |title=Taste Visualization for Pixar's Ratatouille |accessdate=July 9, 2007}}</ref>\nTo create a realistic compost pile, the Art Department photographed fifteen different kinds of produce, such as [[apple]]s, berries, [[banana]]s, [[mushroom]]s, [[Orange (fruit)|oranges]], [[broccoli]], and [[lettuce]], in the process of rotting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.radiofree.com/reviews/ratatoui.shtml |publisher=Radio Free Entertainment |title=Ratatouille (review) |accessdate=July 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe cast members strove to make their French accents authentic yet understandable. [[John Ratzenberger]] notes that he often segued into an Italian accent.<ref name=\"parlez\"/> According to Pixar designer Jason Deamer, \"Most of the characters were designed while Jan [Pinkava] was still directing\u2026 He has a real eye for sculpture.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Barbara Robertson |title=Fish, Rats, Chefs and Robots |publisher=CGSociety |url=http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4144 |accessdate=July 7, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808015610/http://features.cgsociety.org/story_custom.php?story_id=4144# |archive-date=August 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to Pinkava, the critic Anton Ego was designed to resemble a [[vulture]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Bruce R. Miller |title=Book shows how 'Ratatouille' was made |work=Sioux City Journal |date=June 30, 2007 |url=http://www.siouxcityjournal.com/articles/2007/06/29/entertainment/local/8eead5ae7d53b500862573070071c572.txt |accessdate=June 30, 2007}}</ref> To save time, human characters were designed and animated without toes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canmag.com/nw/8040-ratatouille-concept-art-fun-facts |title=Ratatouille Concept Art and Fun Facts! |publisher=CanMag |date=June 16, 2007 |accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRat expert Debbie Ducommun (a.k.a. the \"Rat Lady\") was consulted on rat [[Habit (biology)|habits]] and characteristics.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rat fanciers hope animated film will help their pets shed bad PR |author=Cynthia Hubert |date=June 22, 2007 |work=[[Sacramento Bee]]}}</ref> Along with Ducommun's insight a [[vivarium]] containing pet rats sat in a hallway for more than a year so animators could study the movement of the animals' [[fur]], noses, ears, [[paw]]s, and [[tail]]s as they ran.<ref name=\"animated edit\">{{cite news |author=Anne Neumann |title=Ratatouille Edit Bay Visit! |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=April 25, 2007 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=19939 | accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPromotional material for [[Intel]] credits their platform for a 30 percent performance improvement in rendering software. They used Remy in some of their marketing materials.<ref>{{cite news |last=Desowitz |first=Bill |title=Intel Helps Disney/Pixar Cook Up Ratatouille |url=http://www.awn.com/news/films/intel-helps-disneypixar-cook-ratatouille |accessdate=October 6, 2015 |journal=[[Animation World Network]] |date=July 3, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Desowitz |first=Bill |url=http://www.awn.com/articles/production/iratatouillei-pixar-style-ibon-appetiti/page/2%2C1 |title=Ratatouille Pixar Style: Bon App\u00e9tit |publisher=Animation World Network |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 6, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012034021/http://www.awn.com/articles/production/iratatouillei-pixar-style-ibon-appetiti/page/2%2C1 |archivedate=October 12, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Ratatouille\n| type         = Film score\n| artist       = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = June 26, 2007\n| recorded     = 2006\u20132007\n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Sony Pictures Studios]], [[Culver City, CA]]\n| genre        = [[21st-century classical music|Classical]], [[Film score]]\n| length       = 62:23\n| label        = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer     = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| chronology   = [[Pixar]] soundtrack\n| prev_title   = [[Cars (soundtrack)|Cars]]\n| prev_year    = 2006\n| next_title   = [[WALL-E (soundtrack)|WALL-E]]\n| next_year    = 2008\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n | type       = soundtrack\n | prev_title = [[Mission: Impossible III]]\n | prev_year  = 2006\n | title      = Ratatouille\n | year       = 2007\n | next_title = [[Cloverfield]]\n | next_year  = 2007\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=James Christopher Monger |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/ratatouille-original-soundtrack-mw0000573223 |title=Ratatouille [Original Soundtrack&#93; \u2013 Michael Giacchino &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |date=June 26, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|rev2=''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''\n|rev2score={{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=10111 |title=Empire's Ratatouille Soundtrack Review |work=Empire |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222151217/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=10111 |archivedate=February 22, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|rev3=[[SoundtrackNet]]\n|rev3score={{rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Andrew Granade |url=http://www.soundtrack.net/albums/database/?id=4506 |title=Ratatouille (2007) |publisher=Soundtrack |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n''Ratatouille'' is the second Pixar film to be scored by [[Michael Giacchino]] after ''The Incredibles''. It was also the second Pixar film not to be scored by [[Randy Newman]] or [[Thomas Newman]]. Giacchino had written two themes for Remy, one about his self with the rat colony and the other about his hopes and dreams. He also wrote a buddy theme for both Remy and Linguini that plays when they're together. In addition to the score, Giacchino wrote the main theme song, \"Le Festin\", about Remy and his wishes to be a chef. French artist [[Camille (singer)|Camille]] was hired to perform \"Le Festin\" after Giacchino listened to her music and realized she was perfect for the song; as a result, the song is sung in French in all versions of the film.<ref name=\"slashfilm1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.slashfilm.com/michael-giacchino-talks-music-pixar-d23-expo/ |title=Michael Giacchino Talks The Music Of Pixar [D23 Expo&#93; &#124; /Film |publisher=Slashfilm.com |date=September 2, 2011 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe music for ''Ratatouille'' gave Giacchino his first [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] as well as his first [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Score Soundtrack Album]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0315974/awards/ |title=Michael Giacchino IMDB}}</ref> Giacchino returned to Pixar to score their 2009 blockbuster ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''.<ref name=\"slashfilm1\"/>\n\n{{tracklist\n| title1 = Le Festin\n| note1 = performed by [[Camille (singer)|Camille]]\n| length1 = 2:50\n| title2 = Welcome to Gusteau's\n| length2 = 0:38\n| title3 = This Is Me\n| length3 = 1:41\n| title4 = Granny Get Your Gun\n| length4 = 2:01\n| title5 = 100 Rat Dash\n| length5 = 1:47\n| title6 = Wall Rat\n| length6 = 2:41\n| title7 = Cast of Cooks\n| length7 = 1:41\n| title8 = A Real Gourmet Kitchen\n| length8 = 4:18\n| title9 = Souped Up\n| length9 = 0:50\n| title10 = Is It Soup Yet?\n| length10 = 1:16\n| title11 = A New Deal\n| length11 = 1:56\n| title12 = Remy Drives a Linguini\n| length12 = 2:26\n| title13 = Colette Shows Him le Ropes\n| length13 = 2:56\n| title14 = Special Order\n| length14 = 1:58\n| title15 = Kiss & Vinegar\n| length15 = 1:54\n| title16 = Losing Control\n| length16 = 2:04\n| title17 = Heist to See You\n| length17 = 1:45\n| title18 = The Paper Chase\n| length18 = 1:44\n| title19 = Remy's Revenge\n| length19 = 3:24\n| title20 = Abandoning Ship\n| length20 = 2:55\n| title21 = Dinner Rush\n| length21 = 5:00\n| title22 = Anyone Can Cook\n| length22 = 3:13\n| title23 = End Creditouilles\n| length23 = 9:16\n| title24 = Ratatouille Main Theme\n| length24 = 2:09\n}}\n\n==Release==\n\n''Ratatouille'' was originally going to be released in 2006; however, in December 2004, the date was changed to 2007. This happened because [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]/[[Pixar]] changed the release date of ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', from November 2005 to June 2006, thus pushing ''Ratatouille'' to 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4078711.stm  |title=Pixar-Disney delay Cars release |work=[[BBC News]] |date=December 8, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''Ratatouille''{{'}}s world premiere was on June 22, 2007, at Los Angeles' [[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theater]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/vstory/VR1117967629.html?categoryid=38 |title=Audiences in on 'Ratatouille' pack |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro}}</ref> The commercial release was one week later, with the short film ''[[Lifted (2006 film)|Lifted]]'' preceding ''Ratatouille'' in theaters. Earlier in the year, it had received an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"quint\">{{cite news|author=Eric Vespe|title=Quint orders a giant plate of RATATOUILLE and eats it up!!! |publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |date=June 9, 2007 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/32939 |accessdate=June 10, 2007}}</ref> A [[test screening]] of the film was shown at the Harkins Cine Capri Theater in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] on June 16, 2007, at which a Pixar representative was present to collect viewer feedback.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pixarplanet.com/blog/report-from-pixar-screening-of-ratatouille |title=Report from Pixar Screening of Ratatouille&nbsp;\u2014 Upcoming Pixar |publisher=Pixarplanet.com |accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> Disney CEO Bob Iger announced an upcoming theatrical re-release of the film in 3D at the Disney shareholders meeting in March 2014.<ref name=cartoon>{{cite news |url=http://blog.bcdb.com/incredibles-animated-sequel-6987/ |title=Incredibles Animated Sequel |first=Dave |last=Koch |publisher=[[Big Cartoon DataBase|Big Cartoon News]] |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=March 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140319172802/http://blog.bcdb.com/incredibles-animated-sequel-6987/ |archivedate=March 19, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe trailer for ''Ratatouille'' debuted with the release of its immediate predecessor, ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]''. It depicts an original scene where Remy is caught on the cheese trolley in the restaurant's dining area, sampling the cheese and barely escaping the establishment, intercut with separate scenes of the rat explaining directly to the audience why he is taking such risks. Similar to most of Pixar's teaser trailers, the scene was not present in the final film release.<ref name=\"yahoo1\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/video/ratatouille-trailer-185316448.html |title='Ratatouille' Theatrical Trailer |publisher=Yahoo! |date=April 15, 2013 |accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA second trailer was released on March 23, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Ratatouille Trailer Coming Friday |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=March 19, 2007 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=19432 |accessdate=March 19, 2007}}</ref> The Ratatouille ''Big Cheese Tour'' began on May 11, 2007, with cooking demonstrations and a film preview.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Desowitz|first1=Bill|title=Ratatouille to Kick Off With 'Big Cheese Tour'|url=http://www.awn.com/news/ratatouille-kick-big-cheese-tour|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=August 7, 2016|date=May 11, 2007}}</ref> Voice actor Lou Romano attended the San Francisco leg of the tour for autograph signings.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ratatouille Big Cheese Slide With Lou Romano |publisher=JustPressPlay.net |date=July 16, 2007 |url=http://www.justpressplay.net/movies/ratatouille/news/ratatouille-big-cheese-slide-with-lou-romano.html |accessdate=July 17, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235924/http://www.justpressplay.net/movies/ratatouille/news/ratatouille-big-cheese-slide-with-lou-romano.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Ratatouille-wine.jpg|right|thumb|The front label of the planned ''Ratatouille'' wine to have been promoted by Disney, Pixar, and Costco, and subsequently pulled for its use of a cartoon character]]\nDisney and Pixar were working to bring a French-produced ''Ratatouille''-branded wine to [[Costco]] stores in August 2007, but abandoned plans because of complaints from the California [[Wine Institute (California)|Wine Institute]], citing standards in labelling that restrict the use of cartoon characters to avoid attracting under-age drinkers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/la-fi-ratwine28jul28,0,7091322.story?coll=la-home-center | title=Disney backs out of wine promotion |last=Lifster |first=Marc |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate =August 1, 2007 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, in place of releasing a theatrical trailer, a commercial featuring Remy and Emile was released in cinemas before its release to discourage obtaining unlicensed copies of films.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bvimovies.com/spotlight/anti_piracy.html |title=Ratatouille's Remy fights movie piracy |publisher=The Film Factory |accessdate=December 23, 2007}}</ref> Also, in the United Kingdom, the main characters were used for a commercial for the [[Nissan Note]], with Remy and Emile watching an original commercial for it made for the \"Surprisingly Spacious\" ad campaign and also parodying it, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visit4info.com/details.cfm?adid=49783 |title=Nissan Note Exploding Cars It's Possible |publisher=Visit4Info |accessdate=December 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDisney/Pixar was concerned that audiences, particularly children, would not be familiar with the word \"ratatouille\" and its pronunciation. The title was, therefore, also spelled phonetically within trailers and on posters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deepfocusreview.com/Reviews/ratatouille.asp |title=''Ratatouille'' review |last=Eggert |first=Brian | date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 15, 2007 |publisher=DeepFocusReview.com}}</ref> For similar reasons, in the American release of the film, on-screen text in French was printed in English, such as the title of Gusteau's cookbook and the sign telling kitchen staff to wash their hands, though, in the British English release, these are rendered in French. In Canada, the film was released theatrically with text in English, but on DVD, the majority of the text (including Gusteau's will) was in French.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117967050.html?categoryid=2520&cs=1 | title=Pixar hopes auds find 'Ratatouille' tasty |last=Graser |first=Marc |date=June 15, 2007 |accessdate=October 15, 2007 |work=Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nDisney released ''Ratatouille'' on high-definition [[Blu-ray|Blu-ray Disc]] and DVD in North America on November 6, 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disney/Pixar/Disc_Announcements/Disney_Serves_Up_Ratatouille_on_Blu-ray_this_November/852 | title=Disney Serves Up 'Ratatouille' on Blu-ray this November |publisher=High Def Digest |date=August 10, 2007 |accessdate=August 20, 2007 }}</ref> A new animated short film featuring Remy and Emile entitled ''[[Your Friend the Rat]]'' was included as a special feature, in which the two rats attempt to entreat the viewer, a human, to welcome rats as their friends, demonstrating the benefits and misconceptions of rats towards humanity through several historical examples. The eleven-minute short uses 3D animation, 2D animation, live action and even stop-motion animation, a first for Pixar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?category=0&id=45050&type=0 |title=Rat DVD Has First Pixar 2-D Toon |author=Patrick Lee |date=October 30, 2007 |accessdate=October 30, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230070708/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?category=0&id=45050&type=0 |archivedate=December 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe disc also includes a CG short entitled ''[[Lifted (2006 film)|Lifted]]'', which screened before the film during its theatrical run. It depicts an adolescent [[extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] attempting to abduct a sleeping human. Throughout the sequence, he is graded by an adult extraterrestrial in a manner reminiscent of a [[driver's license|driver's licensing]] exam road test. The entire short contains no dialogue, which is typical of Pixar Shorts not based on existing properties.<ref name=\"pixarplanet1\">{{cite web |url=http://pixarplanet.com/blog/first-lifted-review |title=First Lifted Review&nbsp;\u2014 Upcoming Pixar |publisher=Pixarplanet.com |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Also included among the special features are deleted scenes, a featurette featuring Brad Bird discussing filmmaking and chef [[Thomas Keller]] discussing culinary creativity entitled \"Fine Food and Film\", and four [[Easter egg (media)|easter eggs]]. Although the Region 1 Blu-ray edition has a French audio track, the Region 1 DVD does not, except for some copies marked as for sale only in Canada.<ref name=\"blu-ray1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Ratatouille-Blu-ray/549/ |title=Ratatouille Blu-ray |publisher=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt was released on DVD on November 6, 2007, and earned 4,919,574 units (equivalent to {{USD|73,744,414}}) on its first week (November 6\u201311, 2007) during which it topped the DVD charts. In total it sold 12,531,266 units ({{USD|189,212,532}}) becoming the second-best-selling animated DVD of 2007, both in units sold and sales revenue, behind ''[[Happy Feet]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/annual/2007.php |title=Top-Selling DVDs of 2007 |publisher=the-numbers.com |accessdate=January 11, 2011}}</ref>  Ratatouille was released on [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|4K UHD Blu-ray]] on September 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ratatouille 4K Blu-ray|url=https://www.amazon.com/RATATOUILLE-Blu-ray-Patton-Oswalt/dp/B07T3JPPZN/ref=tmm_frk_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|work=Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|date=September 10, 2019|via=Amazon.com|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 96% approval rating with an average rating of 8.47/10 based on 249 reviews. The site's consensus reads: \"Fast-paced and stunningly animated, ''Ratatouille'' adds another delightfully entertaining entry\u2014and a rather unlikely hero\u2014to the Pixar canon.\"<ref>{{Rotten Tomatoes|ratatouille}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], another review aggregator website which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 top reviews from mainstream critics, calculated a score of 96 out of 100 based on 37 reviews,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/highscores.shtml |title=All-Time High Scores: The Best-Reviewed Movies |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609114144/http://www.metacritic.com/film/highscores.shtml |archivedate=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> the highest of any Pixar film<ref>{{cite web|title=Pixar Animation Studios' Scores|url=http://www.metacritic.com/company/pixar-animation-studios?filter-options=movies&num_items=30&sort_options=metascore|website=Metacritic|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref> and the twenty-first highest film rating on the site.<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Movies of All Time|url=http://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all|website=Metacritic|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called ''Ratatouille'' \"a nearly flawless piece of popular art, as well as one of the most persuasive portraits of an artist ever committed to film\"; echoing the character Anton Ego in the film, he ended his review with a simple \"thank you\" to the creators of the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2007/06/29/movies/29rata.html |title=Voil\u00e0! A Rat for All Seasonings |work=The New York Times |first=A. O. |last=Scott |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=January 15, 2008}}</ref> Wally Hammond of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' gave the film five out of five stars, saying \"A test for tiny tots, a mite nostalgic and as male-dominated as a modern kitchen it may be, but these are mere quibbles about this delightful addition to the Pixar pantheon.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Wally Hammond |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/ratatouille |title=Ratatouille |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |date=October 8, 2007 |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> Andrea Gronvall of the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"Brad Bird's second collaboration with Pixar is more ambitious and meditative than his Oscar-winning ''The Incredibles''.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ratatouille/reviews/?type=top_critics |title=Ratatouille Reviews |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B, saying \"''Ratatouille'' has the Pixar technical magic without, somehow, the full Pixar flavor. It's Brad Bird's genial dessert, not so much incredible as merely sweetly edible.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20044993,00.html |title=Ratatouille |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 6, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"What makes ''Ratatouille'' such a hilarious and heartfelt wonder is the way Bird contrives to let it sneak up on you. And get a load of that score from Michael Giacchino, a perfect complement to a delicious meal.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> [[James Berardinelli]] of ''[[ReelViews]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"For parents looking to spend time in a theater with their kids or adults who want something lighter and less testosterone-oriented than the usual summer fare, ''Ratatouille'' offers a savory main course.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/r/ratatouille.html |title=Reelviews Movie Reviews |publisher=Reelviews.net |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Christy Lemire of the [[Associated Press]] gave the film a positive review, saying \"''Ratatouille'' is free of the kind of gratuitous pop-culture references that plague so many movies of the genre; it tells a story, it's very much of our world but it never goes for the cheap, easy gag.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"The master chefs at Pixar have blended all the right ingredients\u2014abundant verbal and visual wit, genius slapstick timing, a soupcon of Gallic sophistication\u2014to produce a warm and irresistible concoction.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Justin Chang Chief Film Critic @JustinCChang |url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/ratatouille-2-1200558501/ |title=Ratatouille |work=Variety |date=June 18, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMichael Phillips of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"The film may be animated, and largely taken up with rats, but its pulse is gratifyingly human. And you have never seen a computer-animated feature with this sort of visual panache and detail.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips |first=Michael |url=http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-070629-movies-review-ratatouille,0,3953295.story |title=Metromix. Movie review: ''Ratatouille'' |publisher=Web.archive.org |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715125627/http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-070629-movies-review-ratatouille%2C0%2C3953295.story |archivedate=July 15, 2007}}</ref> Rafer Guzman of ''[[Newsday]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"So many computer-animated movies are brash, loud and popping with pop-culture comedy, but ''Ratatouille'' has the warm glow of a favorite book. The characters are more than the sum of their gigabyte-consuming parts \u2013 they feel handcrafted.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Roger Moore of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave the film three out of five stars, saying \"Has Pixar lost its magic recipe? ''Ratatouille'' is filled with fairly generic animated imagery, a few modest chases, a couple of good gags, not a lot of laughs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-06-29/entertainment/RATATOUILLE_1_remy-linguini-rat |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206161721/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-06-29/entertainment/RATATOUILLE_1_remy-linguini-rat |archivedate =February 6, 2014 |title=Rats: You can't carry a 'toon by blathering on about food |work=Orlando Sentinel |first=Roger |last=Moore |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Scott Foundas of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"Bird has taken the raw ingredients of an anthropomorphic-animal kiddie matinee and whipped them into a heady brew about nothing less than the principles of artistic creation.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Olsen |first=Mark |url=http://www.laweekly.com/film/ratatouille-rat-can-cook-2149508 |title=Ratatouille: Rat Can Cook |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> Colin Covert of the ''[[Star Tribune]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"It's not just the computer animation that is vibrantly three-dimensional. It's also the well-rounded characters\u2026 I defy you to name another animated film so overflowing with superfluous beauty.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Steven Rea of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"With ''Ratatouille'', Bird once again delivers not just a great, witty story, but dazzling visuals as well.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Rea |first=Steven |url=http://articles.philly.com/2007-06-29/entertainment/24994660_1_remy-sous-chef-auguste-gusteau |title=You'll smell a ... terrific 'toon, starring a rat  |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> Bill Muller of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' gave the film four-and-a-half stars out of five, saying \"Like the burbling soup that plays a key part in ''Ratatouille'', the movie is a delectable blend of ingredients that tickles the palette and leaves you hungry for more.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/>\n\n[[File:Bradbird.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Brad Bird]] with his second [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]]]]\nRene Rodriguez of the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"''Ratatouille'' is the most straightforward and formulaic picture to date from Pixar Animation Studios, but it is also among the most enchanting and touching.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ae.miami.com/entertainment/ui/miami/movie.html?id=898393&reviewId=22542 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070623044747/http://ae.miami.com/entertainment/ui/miami/movie.html?id=898393&reviewId=22542 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 23, 2007 |title=Movie: Ratatouille |date=December 1, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Jack Mathews of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"The Pixar magic continues with Brad Bird's ''Ratatouille'', a gorgeous, wonderfully inventive computer-animated comedy.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/rat-catch-article-1.219691 |title=A rat to catch! |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 }}</ref> Stephen Whitty of the ''[[Newark Star-Ledger]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"Fresh family fun. Although there are those slightly noxious images of rodents scampering around a kitchen, the movie doesn't stoop to kid-pandering jokes based on backtalk and bodily gases.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> David Ansen of ''[[Newsweek]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"A film as rich as a sauce b\u00e9arnaise, as refreshing as a raspberry sorbet, and a lot less predictable than the damn food metaphors and adjectives all us critics will churn out to describe it. OK, one more and then I'll be done: it's yummy.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ansen |first=David |url=http://www.newsweek.com/ansen-ratatouille-102579 |title=Ansen on 'Ratatouille' |work=Newsweek |date=June 28, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Peter Hartlaub of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"''Ratatouille'' never overwhelms, even though it's stocked with action, romance, historical content, family drama and serious statements about the creation of art.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Hartlaub, Chronicle Pop Culture Critic |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Ratatouille-is-a-feast-for-the-eyes-2583888.php |title=\"Ratatouille\" is a feast for the eyes |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=June 28, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Richard Corliss of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"From the moment Remy enters, crashing, to the final happy fadeout, ''Ratatouille'' parades the brio and depth that set Pixar apart from and above other animation studios.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Corliss |first=Richard |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1630548,00.html |title=Savoring Pixar's Ratatouille |work=TIME |date=June 7, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"A lot of animated movies have inspired sequels, notably ''[[Shrek]]'', but Brad Bird's ''Ratatouille'' is the first one that made me positively desire one.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Ebert |first=Roger |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/ratatouille-2007 |title=Ratatouille Movie Review & Film Summary (2007) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=August 30, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Peter Howell of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, saying \"Had Bird gone the safe route, he would have robbed us of a great new cartoon figure in Remy, who like the rest of the film is rendered with animation that is at once fanciful and life-like. It's also my pick for Pixar's best.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2007/06/29/feast_your_eyes.html |title=Feast your eyes |work=Toronto Star |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJoe Morgenstern of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"The characters are irresistible, the animation is astonishing and the film, a fantasy version of a foodie rhapsody, sustains a level of joyous invention that hasn't been seen in family entertainment since ''The Incredibles''.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Morgenstern |first=Joe |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB118307125242752135?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB118307125242752135.html |title=Pixar Cooks With Joy, Inventiveness In 'Ratatouille' |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Kenneth Turan of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film four-and-a-half stars out of five, saying \"Brad Bird's ''Ratatouille'' is so audacious you have to fall in love with its unlikely hero.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jun/29/entertainment/et-ratatouille29 |title=This is no dirty rat&nbsp;|work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Kenneth |last=Turan}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"''Ratatouille'' is delicious fun sure to be savored by audiences of all ages for its sumptuous visuals, clever wit and irresistibly inspiring tale.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Miriam Di Nunzio of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"''Ratatouille'' will make you wonder why animation needs to hide behind the mantle of 'it's for children, but grownups will like it, too.' This one's for Mom and Dad, and yep, the kids will like it, too.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Chicago Sun-Times |url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/447829,CST-FTR-rat29.article |title=A vermin in Paris finds his inner foodie |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701151410/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/447829%2CCST-FTR-rat29.article |archivedate=July 1, 2007}}</ref> Michael Booth of ''[[The Denver Post]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"Writer and director Brad Bird keeps ''Ratatouille'' moving without resorting to the cute animal jokes or pop-culture wisecracking that ruined so many other recent animated films.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/movies/ci_6245556 |title=Oui! A rich foodie treat, with a great view |work=The Denver Post |date=June 28, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Michael |last=Booth}}</ref> Tom Long of ''[[The Detroit News]]'' gave the film an A, saying \"''Ratatouille'' has the technical genius, emotional core and storytelling audacity to lift it into the ranks of [the best] Pixar films, the cr\u00e8me de la cr\u00e8me of modern animation.\" Liam Lacey of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half stars out of four, saying \"No sketchy backgrounds here\u2014''Ratatouille''{{'}}s scenes feel like deep-focus camera shots. The textures, from the gleam of copper pans to the cobblestone streets, are almost palpable.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> Desson Thomson of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"''Ratatouille'' doesn't center on the over-familiar surfaces of contemporary life. It harks back to Disney's older era when cartoons seemed part of a more elegant world with less edgy characters.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/28/AR2007062802484.html |title='Ratatouille': A Classic Recipe |work=The Washington Post |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 5, 2014 |first=Desson |last=Thomson}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIn its opening weekend in North America, ''Ratatouille'' opened in 3,940 theaters and debuted at number one with $47 million,<ref>{{cite news |author=Pamela McClintock |title=Audiences chow down on \"Ratatouille\" |work=Variety | date=July 1, 2007 | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117967918.html?categoryid=13&cs=1}}</ref> the lowest Pixar opening since ''[[A Bug's Life]]''. However, in France, where the film is set, the film broke the record for the biggest debut for an animated film.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ratatouille Breaks French Record |publisher=Starpulse |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/08/11/ratatouille_breaks_french_record |accessdate=August 13, 2007 |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the film debuted at number one with sales over \u00a34 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukfilmcouncil.org.uk/cinemagoing/boxoffice/?p=D4A1577818d4b19146vpK3480F76&skip= |title=UK Film Box Office: Oct. 12&nbsp;\u2013 Oct. 14 |publisher=[[UK Film Council]] |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102041654/http://www.ukfilmcouncil.org.uk/cinemagoing/boxoffice/?p=D4A1577818d4b19146vpK3480F76&skip= <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=November 2, 2007}}</ref> The film has grossed $206.4 million in the United States and Canada and a total of $620.7 million worldwide, making it the seventh-highest-grossing [[Pixar]] film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/series/Pixar.php |title=Pixar Box Office History |accessdate=July 31, 2010 |publisher=The Numbers}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Ratatouille}}\n''Ratatouille'' won the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]] at the [[80th Academy Awards]] and was nominated for four others: [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], losing to ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]'', ''[[The Bourne Ultimatum (film)|The Bourne Ultimatum]]'' (for both Best Sound Editing and Best Sound Mixing), and ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'', respectively.<ref name=\"academy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |title=Winners and Nominees&nbsp;\u2013 80th Academy Awards |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=January 6, 2009 |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012045551/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |archivedate=October 12, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"oscars2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |title=Nominees & Winners of the 2008 (80th) Academy Awards &#124; Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |date=August 24, 2012 |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012045551/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html |archivedate=October 12, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> At the time, the film held the record for the greatest number of Oscar nominations for a computer animated feature film, breaking the previous record held by ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'', ''[[Finding Nemo]]'', and ''[[The Incredibles]]'' at four nominations, but tied with ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'' for any animated film. In 2008, ''[[WALL-E]]'' surpassed that record with six nominations. As of 2013, ''Ratatouille'' is tied with ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 3]]'' for an animated film with the second-greatest number of Oscar nominations. ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' still holds the record for most Oscar nominations (also 6) for an animated feature film.<ref name=\"oscars2000\"/>\n\nFurthermore, ''Ratatouille'' was nominated for 13 [[Annie Award]]s including twice in the Best Animated Effects, where it lost to ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'', and three times in the Best Voice Acting in an Animated Feature Production for Janeane Garofalo, Ian Holm, and Patton Oswalt, where Ian Holm won the award.<ref name=\"annie\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/35thwinners.html |title=Annie Awards 2007 nominations |publisher=[[ASIFA-Hollywood|International Animated Film Association]] |accessdate=March 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204082048/http://annieawards.org/35thwinners.html |archivedate=December 4, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref> It won the Best Animated Feature Award from multiple associations including the [[Chicago Film Critics Association|Chicago Film Critics]],<ref name=\"chicago\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48:Chicago%20Film%20Critics%20Awards&Itemid=58 |title=Chicago Film Critics Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1998-07 |publisher=Chicago Film Critics Association |accessdate=March 9, 2009}}</ref> the [[National Board of Review]],<ref name=\"national\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/past.cfm?year=2007 |title=Awards for 2007 |publisher=National Board of Review |accessdate=March 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211184324/http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/past.cfm?year=2007 |archivedate=December 11, 2007}}</ref> the Annie Awards,<ref name=\"annie\"/> the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association|Broadcast Film Critics]],<ref name=\"broadcast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfca.org/ccawards/2007.php |title=The 13th Critics Choice Awards winners and nominees |publisher=Broadcast Film Critics Association |accessdate=March 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120530075853/http://www.bfca.org/ccawards/2007.php |archivedate=May 30, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> the [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy of Film and Television (BAFTA)]], and the [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]].<ref name=\"globes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 |title=Hollywood Foreign Press Association 2008 Golden Globe Awards for the year ended December 31, 2007 |publisher=HFPA |date=December 13, 2007 |accessdate=December 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215072618/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=December 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Plagiarized film==\n{{see also|Mockbuster}}\n[[If (magazine)|''If'' magazine]] described ''[[Ratatoing]]'', a 2007 [[Brazil]]ian [[computer animation|computer graphics]] cartoon by [[V\u00eddeo Brinquedo]], as a \"[[ripoff]]\" of ''Ratatouille''.<ref>\"[http://www.ifmagazine.com/review.asp?article=2247 Clip of the Week: RATATOING&nbsp;\u2013 BRAZIL RIPOFF OF RATATOUILLE]\", ''[[If (magazine)|If]]'' {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123055130/http://www.ifmagazine.com/review.asp?article=2247 |date=January 23, 2008 }}</ref> Marco Aur\u00e9lio Can\u00f4nico of the Brazilian newspaper, ''[[Folha de S.Paulo]]'' described ''Ratatoing'' as a derivative of ''Ratatouille''. Can\u00f4nico discussed whether ''Ratatoing'' was similar enough to ''Ratatouille'' to warrant a lawsuit for copyright violation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429215943/http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |title=V\u00eddeo Brinquedo faz sucesso com desenhos como \"Os Carrinhos\" e \"Ratatoing\" |language=Portuguese |work=Folha de S.Paulo |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (Brazil)|Ministry of Culture]] (Brazil) |quote=\"These descriptions bring to mind ''Cars'' and ''Ratatouille'', the latest two feature films by North American giant Pixar, a part of Disney\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429215943/http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |archivedate=April 29, 2008| accessdate= October 6, 2019}}</ref>  The [[Ministry of Culture (Brazil)|Brazilian Ministry of Culture]] posted Marco Aur\u00e9lio Can\u00f4nico's article on its website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |title=V\u00eddeo Brinquedo faz sucesso com desenhos como \"Os Carrinhos\" e \"Ratatoing\" |language=Portuguese |work=Folha de S.Paulo |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture (Brazil)|Ministry of Culture]] (Brazil) |quote=\"These descriptions bring to mind ''Cars'' and ''Ratatouille'', the latest two feature films by North American giant Pixar, a part of Disney\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429215943/http://www.cultura.gov.br/site/?p=107 |archivedate=April 29, 2008}}</ref> To date no sources have been found to indicate that Pixar took legal action.\n\n==Video game==\n{{Main|Ratatouille (video game)}}\nThe primary video game adaptation of the film, titled ''[[Ratatouille (video game)|Ratatouille]]'', was released for all major consoles and handhelds in 2007. A [[Nintendo DS]] exclusive game, titled ''[[Ratatouille: Food Frenzy]]'', was released in October 2007. ''Ratatouille'' is also among the films represented in ''[[Kinect Rush: A Disney-Pixar Adventure]]'', released in March 2012 for [[Xbox 360]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Narcisse |first=Evan |title=Pixar Teams Up With Microsoft For Kinect Rush |url=http://kotaku.com/5866341/pixar-teams-up-with-microsoft-for-kinect-rush/ |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |newspaper=Kotaku |date=December 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe video game based on the movie was released in 2007 for [[Xbox 360]], [[Wii]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[GameCube]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[PlayStation Portable]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]], and [[mobile phone]]s.  A [[PlayStation 3]] version was released on October 23, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/disneypixar-ratatouille|title=Disney/Pixar Ratatouille|website=Metacritic|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> The other versions, however were all released on June 26, 2007.\n\nRemy is featured in the video game ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''. He appears as the head chef for [[Scrooge McDuck|Scrooge McDuck's]] bistro and participates with [[Sora (Kingdom Hearts)|Sora]] in cooking minigames. He is addressed only as \"Little Chef\" in the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/11/17447614/kingdom-hearts-3-gameplay-e3-2018-ratatouille |title=Kingdom Hearts 3 trailer features a new, lovable Pixar character |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=25 January 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media, Inc.]]}}</ref>\n\n==Theme park attraction==\n{{Main|Ratatouille: L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de R\u00e9my}}\nA Disney theme park attraction based on the film has been constructed in [[Walt Disney Studios Park]], [[Disneyland Paris]]. [[Ratatouille: L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de R\u00e9my|''Ratatouille'': L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de R\u00e9my]] is based upon scenes from the film and uses trackless ride technology. In the attraction, riders \"shrink down to the size of a rat\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dlptoday.com/news/walt-disney-studios-park/toon-studio/ratatouille-dark-ride/ |title=Ratatouille: The Adventure&nbsp;\u2013 L'Aventure Totalement Toqu\u00e9e de Remy |work=DLP Today |accessdate=October 9, 2014}}</ref>\nAt the 2017 D23 Expo, Disney announced a similar, ''Ratatouille''-based attraction would be built at the [[France Pavilion at Epcot|France Pavilion]] in [[Epcot|Epcot's]] World Showcase by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/15/business/media/disney-epcot-theme-parks.html|title=Disney Vows to Give Epcot a Magical, Long-Overdue Makeover|first=Brooks|last=Barnes|date=July 15, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Price |first=David |year=2008 |title=The Pixar Touch: The Making of a Company |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |isbn=978-0-307-26575-3 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780307265753 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Ratatouille}}\n{{Commons category|Ratatouille (film)}}\n* {{Official website|http://movies.disney.com/ratatouille}}\n* {{IMDb title|0382932}}\n* {{tcmdb title|641780}}\n* {{Bcdb title|62177}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|ratatouille}}\n* {{Metacritic film|ratatouille}}\n* {{Mojo title|ratatouille}}\n\n{{Ratatouille}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{Brad Bird}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of accolades received by Ratatouille|Awards for ''Ratatouille'']]\n|list=\n{{Academy Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Annie Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Animated Motion Picture}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Animated or Mixed Media Feature Film}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Animated Film}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Animation|Film|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Ratatouille (film)| ]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2007 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about animals]]\n[[Category:Animated films about friendship]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature BAFTA winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Broadcast Film Critics Association Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Film Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Cooking films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about chefs]]\n[[Category:Films about food and drink]]\n[[Category:Films about rats]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Brad Bird]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in restaurants]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Brad Bird]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Ca